                    <h1 class="blog-title">OSINT Reconnaissance Cheatsheet</h1>
                    <div class="blog-meta">
                        <div class="author">
                            <div class="author-avatar">H</div>
                            <span>hackherway</span>
                        </div>
                        <span>May 25, 2026</span>
                        <span>15 min read</span>
                    </div>
                </article>

                <div class="blog-content">
                    <p id="osint-intro">
                        The best attacks start before you touch a single port. OSINT is about building a complete picture of your target from public sources — domains, people, infrastructure, technology, and the mistakes they've already made. Every breached password, every exposed S3 bucket, every employee's LinkedIn post about their "new project" is intelligence. Here's how to gather it systematically.
                    </p>

                    <h2 id="osint-domain">Domain & Subdomain Enumeration</h2>
                    <p>
                        Your target's attack surface is their DNS records. Subdomains host staging environments, admin panels, APIs, and legacy systems that nobody remembers to patch.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Passive subdomain enumeration
subfinder -d target.com -all -o subs.txt
amass enum -passive -d target.com -o amass.txt
assetfinder --subs-only target.com
findomain -t target.com

# Active subdomain enumeration (brute force)
amass enum -active -d target.com -brute -w /usr/share/wordlists/dns.txt
gobuster dns -d target.com -w /usr/share/wordlists/subdomains.txt

# Certificate transparency logs
curl -s "https://crt.sh/?q=%.target.com&output=json" | jq -r '.[].name_value' | sort -u
# Or use certspotter, censys, or certsh

# DNS zone transfer (rare but gold when it works)
dig axfr @ns1.target.com target.com

# Reverse DNS lookup
for ip in $(seq 1 254); do dig -x 192.168.1.$ip +short; done

# Find related domains via WHOIS
whois target.com | grep -i "registrant\|admin\|tech"
# Use the same registrant email to find other domains they own</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="osint-email">Email Harvesting</h2>
                    <p>
                        Emails are usernames, password reset targets, and phishing entry points. The more you collect, the better your social engineering and credential stuffing attacks.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># TheHarvester — classic email/domain harvesting
theHarvester -d target.com -b all
# Sources: baidu, bing, bingapi, bufferoverun, censys, crtsh, dnsdumpster,
#          duckduckgo, google, hackertarget, intelx, linkedin, netcraft,
#          otx, pentesttools, projectdiscovery, qwant, rapiddns, sublist3r,
#          threatcrowd, threatminer, urlscan, virustotal, yahoo

# Hunter.io (requires API key)
curl "https://api.hunter.io/v2/domain-search?domain=target.com&api_key=YOUR_KEY"

# Phonebook.cz
curl "https://api.phonebook.cz/phonebook?domain=target.com"

# Skymem
# skymem.info — search by domain for email addresses

# LinkedIn scraping for corporate emails
# Use tools like linkedint or manual scraping with Sales Navigator
# Pattern: firstname.lastname@target.com, flastname@target.com, etc.

# Verify email validity
# smtp-user-enum, or online tools like verify-email.org</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="osint-breach">Breach Data Analysis</h2>
                    <p>
                        Breached credentials are the fastest way in. If your target's employees reuse passwords (they do), a 2017 breach from some random forum is your ticket to their VPN.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># DeHashed (paid, worth every penny)
curl "https://api.dehashed.com/search?query=email:@target.com" \
  -H "Accept: application/json" \
  -u "your@email.com:api_key"

# Have I Been Pwned (API key required)
curl "https://haveibeenpwned.com/api/v3/breachedaccount/user@target.com" \
  -H "hibp-api-key: YOUR_KEY"

# Leak-Lookup
# leak-lookup.com — search by email or domain

# Public breach dumps (use responsibly)
# Search torrents, forums, and specialized search engines for:
# target.com, @target.com, known employee emails

# Password analysis from breaches
# Once you have hashes, use hashcat or john
# Common patterns: CompanyName2024!, Target123!, Summer2024!

# Credential stuffing
# Use breached credentials against target's login portals
# Tools: cme, crackmapexec, or custom scripts with requests</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="osint-social">Social Media Intelligence</h2>
                    <p>
                        People are the weakest link, and they advertise their weaknesses on social media. Job postings reveal technology stacks, vacation photos reveal badge designs, and "first day" posts reveal internal systems.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># LinkedIn reconnaissance
# Search for employees by title: "system administrator", "devops", "security"
# Look for recent departures — they often still have access
# Check "About" sections for technology mentions

# Twitter / X reconnaissance
# Search: site:twitter.com "target.com" OR "@target" "password" OR "vpn" OR "aws"
# Use advanced search: from:employee_handle "internal tool"

# GitHub reconnaissance (detailed section below)
# Search for leaked credentials, internal repositories, exposed keys

# Instagram / Facebook
# Geolocation tagging on office photos
# Badge designs in "first day" or "team outing" posts
# Whiteboards with architecture diagrams in background

# Shodan images
# shodan.io/images — search by organization for exposed webcams, industrial systems

# Wayback Machine
# web.archive.org — find old versions of the site, exposed files, changed content
# Use waybackurls to extract all archived URLs
waybackurls target.com > wayback.txt

# Google Dorks
site:target.com filetype:pdf "confidential"
site:target.com filetype:doc "password"
site:target.com inurl:admin
site:target.com intitle:"index of" "config"
site:pastebin.com "target.com"
site:github.com "target.com" "password" OR "api_key" OR "secret"</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="osint-tech">Technology Stack Fingerprinting</h2>
                    <p>
                        Knowing what technologies your target uses tells you exactly what vulnerabilities to look for. A Django app has different weaknesses than a .NET Core API.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Wappalyzer (browser extension or CLI)
wappalyzer https://target.com

# BuiltWith
# builtwith.com — comprehensive technology profile

# WhatWeb
whatweb https://target.com

# Nmap scripts
nmap -p80,443 --script http-title,http-enum,http-headers,http-methods target.com

# Shodan
# shodan.io — search by domain, IP, or organization
# Find exposed services, versions, and misconfigurations

# Censys
# censys.io — similar to Shodan, better for certificate data

# Favicon analysis
# Hash the favicon and search on Shodan/Censys for related assets
# curl -s https://target.com/favicon.ico | md5sum

# Error pages
# Trigger 404s and 500s to see stack traces revealing frameworks
# https://target.com/nonexistent
# https://target.com/admin'

# API documentation
# /swagger-ui.html, /api-docs, /v2/api-docs, /openapi.json
# /graphql, /api/graphql
# Reveal endpoints, parameters, and authentication schemes</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="osint-github">GitHub Reconnaissance</h2>
                    <p>
                        Developers leak everything on GitHub. API keys, database credentials, internal documentation, and hardcoded passwords in commit history. GitHub search is your best friend.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># GitHub dorks
org:target-org "password"
org:target-org "api_key"
org:target-org "secret"
org:target-org "AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID"
org:target-org "private_key"
org:target-org "jdbc:mysql"
org:target-org "mongodb://"
org:target-org "redis://"

# Search in commit history
git log --all --source --remotes -- '*.env'
git log --all -p -- '*.json' | grep -i "password\|secret\|key"

# TruffleHog — scan for secrets in repos
trufflehog git https://github.com/target-org/repo.git
trufflehog filesystem /path/to/repo

# GitLeaks — similar secret scanner
gitleaks detect --source /path/to/repo

# GitHub API for enumeration
curl "https://api.github.com/orgs/target-org/repos?per_page=100"
curl "https://api.github.com/orgs/target-org/members?per_page=100"
curl "https://api.github.com/users/employee/repos?per_page=100"

# Gist search
curl "https://api.github.com/gists/public?per_page=100" | grep target-org

# Commit history analysis
# Even if secrets are removed, they're in the git history
# git log -p | grep -i "password\|secret\|token"</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="osint-cloud">Cloud Asset Discovery</h2>
                    <p>
                        Cloud misconfigurations are the new open ports. S3 buckets, Azure blobs, GCP storage — they're all publicly accessible if someone clicked the wrong checkbox.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># AWS S3 bucket enumeration
# Common naming patterns:
# target.com, target-com, target-backup, target-data, target-dev
# Use s3scanner or manual enumeration

# S3 bucket brute force
curl https://target.s3.amazonaws.com
curl https://s3.amazonaws.com/target
curl https://s3.amazonaws.com/target-backup

# Grayhat Warfare
# grayhatwarfare.com — search public S3 buckets by keyword

# Bucket enumeration tools
s3scanner scan --buckets buckets.txt
aws s3 ls s3://target-bucket --no-sign-request

# Azure blob storage
# https://target.blob.core.windows.net/container
# https://target.queue.core.windows.net/

# GCP storage
# https://storage.googleapis.com/target-bucket

# Cloudflare enumeration
# Search for origin IPs bypassing Cloudflare
# Use censys, shodan, or historical DNS data
# Once you have the origin IP, attack it directly

# Terraform state files
# terraform.tfstate often contains plaintext secrets
# Search: site:target.com filetype:tfstate
# Or check GitHub for .tfstate files</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="osint-checklist">Quick Checklist</h2>
                    <ul>
                        <li><code>subfinder -d target.com -all</code> — subdomain enumeration</li>
                        <li><code>amass enum -passive -d target.com</code> — comprehensive DNS data</li>
                        <li><code>theHarvester -d target.com -b all</code> — email and domain harvesting</li>
                        <li><code>whois target.com</code> — registrant information</li>
                        <li><code>dig axfr @ns1.target.com target.com</code> — zone transfer attempt</li>
                        <li>Search breach databases for @target.com emails</li>
                        <li>Search Have I Been Pwned for key employee emails</li>
                        <li>LinkedIn reconnaissance for employee roles and technology mentions</li>
                        <li>Twitter/X search for leaked information or complaints about internal tools</li>
                        <li>GitHub search for org:target-org with keywords: password, api_key, secret</li>
                        <li>Shodan search for target IPs and exposed services</li>
                        <li>Censys search for certificate data and cloud assets</li>
                        <li>Google dorks for exposed documents, admin panels, and directory listings</li>
                        <li>Wayback Machine for historical site versions and exposed files</li>
                        <li>S3 bucket enumeration with common naming patterns</li>
                        <li>Grayhat Warfare for public cloud storage</li>
                        <li>Wappalyzer / WhatWeb for technology fingerprinting</li>
                        <li>TruffleHog / GitLeaks for secret detection in repos</li>
                        <li>Search Pastebin, GitHub Gists, and forums for leaked credentials</li>
                    </ul>

                    <blockquote>
                        "OSINT isn't about finding secrets. It's about finding the people who accidentally published them and the systems that never should have been public."
                    </blockquote>
